{"title_page": "KFRQ", "text_new": "{{short description|Radio station in Harlingen, Texas}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| image            = File:Q945AllRockAllTheTimeLogo.jpg\n| name             = KFRQ\n| city             = [[Harlingen, Texas]]\n| area             = [[Rio Grande Valley]]\n| branding         = ''Q94.5''\n| slogan           = All Rock All the time\n| frequency        = 94.5 [[Megahertz|MHz]]\n| airdate          = 1960 (as KELT)\n| format           = [[Classic rock]]\n| erp              = 100,000 [[watt]]s\n| haat             = {{convert|453|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| class            = C\n| facility_id      = 56484\n| coordinates      = \n| callsign_meaning =\n| former_callsigns = KELT-FM (1967\u20131972, 1983\u20131986)<br>KELT (1960\u20131967, 1972\u20131983, 1986\u20131992)\n| affiliations     = \n| owner            = [[Entravision Communications]]<!-- Please do not change ownership to MBM Corporative, LLC. The station is still owned and operated by Entravision. -->\n| licensee         = Entravision Holdings, LLC\n| sister_stations  = [[KKPS]], [[KNVO-FM]], [[KVLY (FM)|KVLY]]<!-- Please do not add KESO, and KZSP. Those stations are not owned and operated by Entravision. -->\n| webcast          = [http://q945therock.com/streaming1.php Listen Live]\n| website          = [https://q945therock.com/ q945therock.com]\n}}\n\n'''KFRQ''' (94.5 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) is a [[radio station]] broadcasting a [[classic rock]] format. Licensed to [[Harlingen, Texas]], United States, the station serves the [[Rio Grande Valley]] area.  The station is currently owned by [[Entravision Communications|Entravision]].<!-- Please do not change ownership to MBM Corporative, LLC. The station is still owned and operated by Entravision. --><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?call=KFRQ |title=KFRQ Facility Record |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division }}</ref> It shares a studio with its sister stations in [[McAllen, Texas]], while its transmitter is located in [[La Feria, Texas]].\n\n==History==\nThe station began around 1960 as easy listening station KELT-FM and was co-owned with KGBT [[KGBT (AM)|AM]] and [[KGBT-TV|television]]. Some of the TV personalities such as anchorman Frank \"FM\" Sullivan and weathercaster Larry James hosted music programs on the station.  Frank's wife Hilda Sullivan would anchor locally produced newsbreaks called \"Micronews.\"  The station would soon automate and update the programming to adult contemporary using Drake-Chenault's \"Hit Parade\". The station would later change to country music as \"K-Frog\" and would on March 1, 1992 change its call sign to the current KFRQ. On January 1, 1995 the station changed formats to rock under the direction of Program Director Alan Sells. On December 15, 2017, Entravision conducted a corporate restructure, firing over half the air staff, including their morning show hosts for over 20 years, Big Al and Charlie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=56484&Callsign=KFRQ |title=KFRQ Call Sign History |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division }}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2020 KFRQ shifted their format from Active Rock to Classic Rock, still under the \"Q94.5\" name.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/185989/kvly-teasing-monday-revamp/ Entravision Flips KVLY To AC And Shifts KFRQ To Classic Rock] Radioinsight - April 13, 2020</ref> The change comes two weeks after sister station [[KKPS]] changed their format from [[Regional Mexican]] to [[Contemporary hit radio|Bilingual CHR]]. Sister station [[KVLY (FM)|KVLY]] also switched their format from [[Contemporary hit radio]] back to [[Adult Contemporary]] the same day. With the change, this brought back the Classic rock format to the Rio Grande Valley for the first since 2015, when [[iHeartMedia]]-owned station [[KQXX-FM]] dropped that format for a simulcast of Hot AC-formatted station [[KHKZ]], also owned by iHeartMedia. [[KRIX]] also flipped to Classic Rock on the same day, thus sparking a \u201cClassic Rock\u201d war between both stations.\n\n==Previous Logos==\n[[File:KFRQ logo.png|245px]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://q945therock.com KFRQ - Official Website]\n{{FM station data|KFRQ}}\n\n{{McAllen-Brownsville-Harlingen Radio}}\n{{Classic Rock Radio Stations in Texas}}\n{{Entravision Communications}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kfrq}}\n[[Category:Radio stations in Texas|FRQ]]\n[[Category:Classic rock radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Harlingen, Texas]]\n[[Category:Entravision Communications stations]]\n\n{{Texas-radio-station-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Radio station in Harlingen, Texas}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| image            = File:Q945AllRockAllTheTimeLogo.jpg\n| name             = KFRQ\n| city             = [[Harlingen, Texas]]\n| area             = [[Rio Grande Valley]]\n| branding         = ''Q94.5''\n| slogan           = All Rock All the time\n| frequency        = 94.5 [[Megahertz|MHz]]\n| airdate          = 1960 (as KELT)\n| format           = [[Classic rock]]\n| erp              = 100,000 [[watt]]s\n| haat             = {{convert|453|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| class            = C\n| facility_id      = 56484\n| coordinates      = \n| callsign_meaning =\n| former_callsigns = KELT-FM (1967\u20131972, 1983\u20131986)<br>KELT (1960\u20131967, 1972\u20131983, 1986\u20131992)\n| affiliations     = \n| owner            = [[Entravision Communications]]<!-- Please do not change ownership to MBM Corporative, LLC. The station is still owned and operated by Entravision. -->\n| licensee         = Entravision Holdings, LLC\n| sister_stations  = [[KKPS]], [[KNVO-FM]], [[KVLY (FM)|KVLY]]<!-- Please do not add KESO, and KZSP. Those stations are not owned and operated by Entravision. -->\n| webcast          = [http://q945therock.com/streaming1.php Listen Live]\n| website          = [https://q945therock.com/ q945therock.com]\n}}\n\n'''KFRQ''' (94.5 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) is a [[radio station]] broadcasting a [[classic rock]] format. Licensed to [[Harlingen, Texas]], United States, the station serves the [[Rio Grande Valley]] area.  The station is currently owned by [[Entravision Communications|Entravision]].<!-- Please do not change ownership to MBM Corporative, LLC. The station is still owned and operated by Entravision. --><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?call=KFRQ |title=KFRQ Facility Record |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division }}</ref> It shares a studio with its sister stations in [[McAllen, Texas]], while its transmitter is located in [[La Feria, Texas]].\n\n==History==\nThe station began around 1960 as easy listening station KELT-FM and was co-owned with KGBT [[KGBT (AM)|AM]] and [[KGBT-TV|television]]. Some of the TV personalities such as anchorman Frank \"FM\" Sullivan and weathercaster Larry James hosted music programs on the station.  Frank's wife Hilda Sullivan would anchor locally produced newsbreaks called \"Micronews.\"  The station would soon automate and update the programming to adult contemporary using Drake-Chenault's \"Hit Parade\". The station would later change to country music as \"K-Frog\" and would on March 1, 1992 change its call sign to the current KFRQ. On January 1st, 1995 the station changed formats to rock under the direction of Program Director Alan Sells. On December 15, 2017, Entravision conducted a corporate restructure, firing over half the air staff, including their morning show hosts for over 20 years, Big Al and Charlie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=56484&Callsign=KFRQ |title=KFRQ Call Sign History |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division }}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2020 KFRQ shifted their format from Active Rock to Classic Rock, still under the \"Q94.5\" name.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/185989/kvly-teasing-monday-revamp/ Entravision Flips KVLY To AC And Shifts KFRQ To Classic Rock] Radioinsight - April 13, 2020</ref> The change comes two weeks after sister station [[KKPS]] changed their format from [[Regional Mexican]] to [[Contemporary hit radio|Bilingual CHR]]. Sister station [[KVLY (FM)|KVLY]] also switched their format from [[Contemporary hit radio]] back to [[Adult Contemporary]] the same day. With the change, this brought back the Classic rock format to the Rio Grande Valley for the first since 2015, when [[iHeartMedia]]-owned station [[KQXX-FM]] dropped that format for a simulcast of Hot AC-formatted station [[KHKZ]], also owned by iHeartMedia. [[KRIX]] also flipped to Classic Rock on the same day, thus sparking a \u201cClassic Rock\u201d war between both stations.\n\n==Previous Logos==\n[[File:KFRQ logo.png|245px]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://q945therock.com KFRQ - Official Website]\n{{FM station data|KFRQ}}\n\n{{McAllen-Brownsville-Harlingen Radio}}\n{{Classic Rock Radio Stations in Texas}}\n{{Entravision Communications}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kfrq}}\n[[Category:Radio stations in Texas|FRQ]]\n[[Category:Classic rock radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Harlingen, Texas]]\n[[Category:Entravision Communications stations]]\n\n{{Texas-radio-station-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ThePersecuted", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:MOS:DATESNO", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KFRQ"}
{"title_page": "Grand Concourse (Bronx)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Boulevard in the Bronx, New York}}\n{{Infobox street\n| name                    = Grand Concourse\n| marker_image            = \n| native_name             =\n| native_name_lang        =\n| alternate_name          = Grand Boulevard and Concourse\n| image                   = 1650 Grand Concourse.jpg\n| image_size              = 300px\n| image_alt               =\n| image_map               = \n| caption                 = Looking southward from 179th Street with [[Manhattan]] in the background\n| map_type                =\n| map_size                = \n| map_caption             = \n| map_alt                 = \n| other_name              =\n| former_names            = \n| part_of                 =\n| namesake                = \n| type                    =\n| owner                   = [[City of New York]]\n| maint                   = [[NYCDOT]]\n| length_mi               = 5.2\n| length_ref              = <ref name=google/>\n| length_notes            =\n| width                   =\n| area                    =\n| addresses               =\n| location                = [[Bronx]], [[New York City]]\n| postal_code             =\n| metro                   = \n| coordinates             = \n| direction_a             = South\n| terminus_a              = {{jct|state=NY|I|87|road=138th Street}} in [[Mott Haven, Bronx|Mott Haven]]\n| direction_b             = North\n| terminus_b              = {{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Mosholu}} in [[Bedford Park, Bronx|Bedford Park]]\n| junction                = \n| east                    =\n| west                    =\n| designer                = Louis Aloys Risse\n| main_contractor         = \n| cost                    =\n| references              =\n| commissioning_date      =\n| construction_start_date = {{Start date|1894}}\n| completion_date         = {{Start date|1909}}\n| inauguration_date       = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| demolition_date         =\n| known_for               =\n| status                  =\n| embedded =\n{{Infobox NRHP | name =Grand Concourse Historic District\n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type = hd  | nocat = yes\n  | image = Grand Concourse 2007-11.jpg\n  | caption = Art Deco apartment buildings along Grand Concourse\n  | location= [[The Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|49|50|N|73|55|15|W|region:US-NY_type:landmark_dim:10km|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = New York City\n  | area =\n| architect= Multiple\n| architecture= Late 19th and 20th Century Revivals, Art Deco, Other\n | added = August 24, 1987\n | governing_body = Local\n | refnum=87001388<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n  | designated_other2_name = NYC Landmark\n  | designated_other2_date = October 25, 2011\n  | designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n  | designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n  | designated_other2_number = 2403\n  | designated_other2_color = #ffe978\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Grand Concourse''' (also known as the '''Grand Boulevard and Concourse''') is a {{Convert|5.2|mi||-long|abbr=|adj=mid}} thoroughfare in the [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[the Bronx]] in [[New York City]]. Grand Concourse runs through several neighborhoods, including [[Bedford Park, Bronx|Bedford Park]], [[Concourse, Bronx|Concourse]], [[Highbridge, Bronx|Highbridge]], [[Fordham, Bronx|Fordham]], [[Mott Haven, Bronx|Mott Haven]], [[Norwood, Bronx|Norwood]] and [[Tremont, Bronx|Tremont]]. For most of its length, the Concourse is {{Convert|180|ft||abbr=}} wide.\n\nThe Grand Concourse was designed by Louis Aloys Risse, an immigrant from [[Saint-Avold]], [[Lorraine]], [[France]]. Risse first conceived of the road in 1890, and the Concourse was built between 1894 and 1909, with an additional extension in 1927. The development of the Concourse led to the construction of apartment buildings surrounding the boulevard, and by 1939 it was called \"the [[Park Avenue]] of middle-class Bronx residents\".<ref name=\"Moore 1981\" /> A period of decline followed in the 1960s and 1970s, when these residences became dilapidated and the Concourse was redesigned to be more motorist-friendly. Renovation and redevelopment started in the 1980s, and a portion of the Grand Concourse was reconstructed starting in the 2000s.\n\nThe southern portion of the Grand Concourse is surrounded by several historically important residential buildings, which were listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1987 as part of the '''Grand Concourse Historic District'''. In 2011, the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] designated numerous buildings around the Grand Concourse as part of a city landmark district. Additionally, several individual points of interest are located on or near the Concourse, including the [[Bronx Museum of the Arts]] and [[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]].\n\n== Description ==\nThe Grand Concourse's southern terminus is at 138th Street. Shortly afterward, it merges with the entrance ramp to southbound [[Major Deegan Expressway]] ([[Interstate 87 (New York)|I-87]]), as well as the exit ramp from northbound I-87. The Grand Concourse continues as a divided eight-lane avenue, with two to three traffic lanes in each direction, until 161st Street.<ref name=google/> North of there, the [[frontage road|service roads]] in each direction begin, and a unidirectional buffered [[bike lane]] runs on the left edge of either service road.<ref name=\"NYC Bike Map\">{{cite web | title=NYC DOT Bicycle Map 2018 | website=NYC.gov |publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]] |date=2018 | url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/bikemap-2018.pdf| access-date=October 17, 2018}}</ref> The Grand Concourse is briefly a ten-lane boulevard with four roadways, two in each direction, until just south of 165th Street. There, the northbound and southbound inner roadways merge into a five-lane undivided roadway with two lanes in each direction and a left-turn lane and painted median in the center.<ref name=google/> The buffered bike lanes on each service road end at 171st Street, and conventional bike lanes start on the right lane of the respective service roads.<ref name=\"NYC Bike Map\"/> This configuration with three roadways (two service roads and one main road) continues north until [[Mosholu Parkway]], where the Grand Concourse ends. At [[Fordham Road]], the main road passes underneath in a [[grade-separated junction]], while the service roads intersect with Fordham Road.<ref name=\"google\">{{google maps|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Grand+Concourse,+Bronx,+NY/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x89c2f46bc54b9a29:0xdb71eee2ad49db66?sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiQ7pn9uI3eAhWBl-AKHTmxCOMQ8gEwAHoECAAQAQ|title=Grand Concourse, Bronx, NY|access-date=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBetween approximately 161st and 204th Streets, the [[New York City Subway]]'s [[IND Concourse Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Concourse}}) runs under the Grand Concourse. The [[IRT Jerome Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Jerome south}}) also runs underneath the boulevard for a short section south of 149th Street.<ref name=google/> The [[Bx1 (New York City bus)|Bx1]] local bus and the [[BxM4 (New York City bus)|BxM4]] express bus run the entire length of the Grand Concourse, while the [[Bx2 (New York City bus)|Bx2]] local bus runs on the Concourse north of 149th Street.<ref>{{cite NYC bus map|Bx}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Construction ===\n[[File:The_Great_north_side,_or,_Borough_of_the_Bronx,_New_York_(1897)_(14765078865).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Intersection plan, 1892]]\nRisse first conceived of the road in 1890, as a means of connecting the borough of [[Manhattan]] to the northern Bronx.<ref>[http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/03/18/looking-back-at-the-grand-concourses-first-century/ ''The New York Times'', March 18, 2009] Looking back at the Grand Concourse First Century</ref> Construction began on the Grand Concourse in 1894 and it was opened to traffic in November 1909. Built during the height of the [[City Beautiful movement]], it was modeled on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in Paris but is considerably larger, stretching four miles (6&nbsp;km) in length, measuring {{convert|180|ft|m}} across, and separated into three roadways by tree-lined dividers, so some minor streets did not cross the Concourse. The cost of the project was $14 million (worth ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|14000000|1900}}}} today).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westegg.com/inflation/ |title=The Inflation Calculator |accessdate=April 13, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5QVXNUZmW?url=http://www.westegg.com/inflation/ |archivedate=July 21, 2007 }}</ref> \n\nThe Grand Concourse originally stretched from Bronx Borough Hall at 161st Street north to [[Van Cortlandt Park]]. It was expanded southward to 138th Street in 1927 after Mott Avenue was widened to accommodate the boulevard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forgotten-ny.com/2011/10/back-on-course-revisiting-the-grand-concourse|title=BACK ON \u2018COURSE: Revisiting the Grand Concourse|publisher=|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> Evidence of the Grand Concourse extension's old name is present at the [[149th Street\u2013Grand Concourse station]], where there are signs reading \"Mott Avenue\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Development ===\nThe [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]]'s Jerome Avenue Line opened a few blocks west of the Grand Concourse in 1917, initiating a housing boom amongst upwardly mobile, predominantly Jewish and Italian, families who were fleeing the crowded tenements of Manhattan. In 1923, [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|Yankee Stadium]] opened near the Grand Concourse at 161st Street, down the hill from the [[Concourse Plaza Hotel]]. South of Fordham Road, the palatial [[Paradise Theater (Bronx)|Loew's Paradise]] theater, one of the [[Loew's Wonder Theatres]] and at one time the largest movie theater in New York City, was constructed in 1929.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fire Badly Damages Paradise Theater, a Bronx Landmark|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/06/nyregion/fire-damages-paradise-theater-a-bronx-landmark.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDevelopment of the Concourse was further encouraged by the opening of the [[Independent Subway System]]'s Concourse Line in 1933. By the mid-1930s, almost three hundred apartment buildings had been built along the Concourse. Customarily five or six stories high with wide entrance courtyards bordered with grass and shrubs, among these apartments are many of the finest examples of [[Art Deco]] and [[Art Moderne]] architecture in the United States. Even though the [[Great Depression in the United States|Great Depression]], which was happening at the time, ended the period of tremendous growth, privately financed apartment buildings continued to be constructed. Furthermore, work was done on the Grand Concourse as part of WPA programs.<ref name=\"encnyc\">{{cite enc-nyc2}}</ref> During this period, the Bronx had more amenities than other boroughs: in 1934, almost 99% of residences had private bathrooms, and 95% had central heating.<ref>{{cite web|title=ONE HUNDRED YEARS OF THE BRONX |url=http://www.bronxhistoricalsociety.org/journal/historyofthebronxjournal.html |accessdate=October 11, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021042529/http://www.bronxhistoricalsociety.org/journal/historyofthebronxjournal.html |archivedate=October 21, 2007 }}</ref> In the 1939 [[American Guide Series|''WPA Guide to New York City'']], the Grand Concourse was described as \"the [[Park Avenue]] of middle-class Bronx residents, and the lease to an apartment in one of its many large buildings is considered evidence of at least moderate business success.\"<ref name=\"Moore 1981\">{{cite book|last=Moore|first=D.D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=POfJa1DJz9oC&pg=PA76|title=At Home in America: Second Generation New York Jews|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=1981|isbn=978-0-231-05063-0|series=Columbia history of urban life|page=76|access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite fednyc|page=517}}</ref>\n\n=== Decline ===\nIn 1941, the New York City Planning Department proposed converting the boulevard into an expressway, in order to connect the [[Major Deegan Expressway]] and the proposed Park Avenue Expressway to the south with the [[Mosholu Parkway]] to the north. However, these plans were abandoned following the southern extension of the [[Bronx River Parkway]] in the 1940s and the extension of the Major Deegan Expressway to the north in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycroads.com/roads/grand-concourse/|title=Grand Concourse Express Highway (NY 22 and NY 100, unbuilt)|publisher=|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe south and central Bronx rapidly deteriorated in the 1960s, as there was general disinvestment in the region's real estate, exacerbated by [[urban renewal]] and [[redlining]] programs.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 18\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2011|ps=.|p=18}}</ref><ref name=\"Gonzalez p. 111\">{{harvnb|Gonzalez|2006|ps=.|p=111}}</ref> Many white residents of the South Bronx left for suburban areas in a process known as [[white flight]]; they were helped by the construction of the [[Interstate Highway System]].<ref name=\"Gonzalez p. 148\">{{harvnb|Gonzalez|2006|ps=.|p=148}}</ref><ref name=\"Rosenblum p. 179\">{{harvnb|Rosenblum|2009|ps=.|p=179}}</ref> At the same time, [[African Americans]] and [[Stateside Puerto Ricans|Puerto Ricans]] were moving to the Bronx for blue-collar jobs; however, these jobs were increasingly being shifted to the suburbs, the [[Southern United States]], and other countries.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 18\" /><ref name=\"Rosenblum p. 179\" /> Racial discrimination against these demographic groups prevented them from moving to the suburbs, forcing them into deteriorating urban housing stock.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 18\" /><ref name=\"Rosenblum p. 109\">{{harvnb|Rosenblum|2009|ps=.|p=109}}</ref> The buildings around the Concourse thus came to be perceived as old and low-rent, and subsequent cycles of disinvestment led landlords on the Concourse to pay decreasingly less attention to their housing stock,<ref name=\"Gonzalez p. 148\" /> while banks and insurance companies failed to give financial support to these neighborhoods.<ref name=\"Gonzalez p. 181\">{{harvnb|Gonzalez|2006|ps=.|p=181}}</ref> Further outward migration between 1968 and 1970 drained the areas along the Grand Concourse of most of its remaining middle-class residents. Many buildings in the area were damaged by arson, vandalism, and a lack of maintenance.\n\nThe road itself was modified to be more hospitable to motorists.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 21\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2011|ps=.|p=21}}</ref> During the 1960s, the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] removed the grass median on the Concourse and replaced it with cement that was painted green.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Williams|first=Timothy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/09/nyregion/a-resurgence-in-the-bronx-is-finally-putting-the-grand-back-in-the.html|title=A Resurgence in the Bronx Is Finally Putting the Grand Back in the Concourse|date=May 9, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 24, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By the 1980s, ''The New York Times'' characterized the Concourse as \"a driver\u2019s paradise\". Traffic lights were timed so that motorists received a \"[[green wave]]\", moving through intersections at a time. Meanwhile, pedestrian crossings and trees were eliminated, and green highway signs were placed on the Concourse.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Kugel|first=Seth|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/16/nyregion/neighborhood-report-grand-concourse-making-once-noble-boulevard-look-less-like.html|title=NEIGHBORHOOD REPORT: GRAND CONCOURSE; Making a Once-Noble Boulevard Look Less Like the Interstate...|date=May 16, 2004|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 24, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Restoration ===\nDuring the 1980s, landlords along the Concourse and elsewhere in the South Bronx began rehabilitating their buildings.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 20\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2011|ps=.|p=20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Goodman|first=George W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/12/realestate/rehabilitation-holding-bronx-blight-at-bay.html|title=Rehabilitation Holding Bronx Blight at Bay|date=June 12, 1983|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 24, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[Bronx Museum of the Arts]], was one of the institutions to move to the area, relocating in 1982 to a former synagogue at Grand Concourse and 167th Street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 20\" /> The city created the \"Special Grand Concourse Preservation District\" in 1989 to preserve the character of residential buildings on the Concourse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zr.planning.nyc.gov/index.php/article-xii/chapter-2|title=Chapter 2 {{!}} Zoning Resolution: Special Grand Concourse Preservation District|last=|first=|date=September 28, 1989|website=zr.planning.nyc.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref> This led to new building developments on the Concourse starting in the 1990s,<ref name=\"Rosenblum p. 221\">{{harvnb|Rosenblum|2009|ps=.|p=221}}</ref> including the [[Rafael Vi\u00f1oly]]-designed Bronx Housing Courthouse at 1118 Grand Concourse.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 20\" /> In addition, basement stores started opening on the Concourse in the 1980s, serving the predominantly minority communities around the boulevard. By 2003, a ''New York Times'' writer observed that \"every block between 161st Street and 196th Street now has a grocery, a barber shop, a travel agency or a medical clinic\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Berger|first=Joseph|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/18/nyregion/concourse-gets-used-commerce-street-s-historic-character-clashes-with-modernity.html|title=Concourse Gets Used To Commerce; Street's Historic Character Clashes With Modernity|date=September 18, 2003|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 24, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Boulevard reconstruction ====\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1 = Grand Conc 165 jeh.JPG\n| caption1 = Renovated intersection with [[161st Street (Bronx)|161st Street]] in 2008\n| image2 = GC under Fordham Road jeh.JPG\n| caption2 = Unrenovated section at East 187th Street\n| total_width = 400\n| alt1 = \n}}\n\nBy the early 1990s, politicians and community advocates strove to make the Concourse more usable for pedestrians. At that time, the Concourse was one of the most dangerous streets in New York City, with twelve pedestrians dying in 1991, rivaling the reputation of [[Queens Boulevard]] as the \"Boulevard of Death\".<ref name=\":4\" /> In 1992, the [[New York City Department of Transportation]] (NYCDOT) conducted a study of the Grand Concourse, which resulted in improvements such as left-turn signals; pedestrian barriers; roadway markings; repainted crosswalks; and new and improved signage. These improvements continued along the entire corridor through 2006.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/safetyrpt07_1.pdf|title=SAFE STREETS NYC: The Bronx|last=|first=|date=June 2007|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|pages=16\u201330|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref>{{Rp|16\u201319}} As an experiment, the NYCDOT also completely rebuilt the section between [[161st Street (Bronx)|161st Street]] and 167th Streets starting in 1999, as a \"demonstration\" project.<ref name=\":3\" />{{rp|20\u201326}} The Grand Concourse underwent an $18 million restoration and landscaping to widen and landscape the medians; improve lighting; add new signage; build pedestrian planters in the medians; and add bike lanes. This resulted in a 69% drop in accidents along this section between 1998 and 2005.<ref name=\":3\" />{{rp|20\u201322}} The final part of the demonstration project was completed in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/161_166grandconcourse.pdf|title=Grand Concourse 2008|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the success of the \"demonstration\" reconstruction, the NYCDOT unveiled a four-phase capital project between 161st Street and [[Fordham Road]] as part of a capital project, which would receive funding directly from the city. Tthe demonstration project was the first phase of the capital project. A reconstruction of the Grand Concourse between 166th and 171st Street began in 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/2013-02-grand-concourse.pdf|title=HWXP136A RECONSTRUCTION OF GRAND CONCOURSE SERVICE ROADS EAST 166TH STREET TO EAST 171ST STREET|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]] |date=February 2013|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> and was finished in June 2017.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/grand-concourse-jan2017.pdf|title=GRAND CONCOURSE PHASE 4 Community Workshop|last=|first=|date=January 19, 2017|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|access-date=March 6, 2017}}</ref> Funding is being allocated for a reconstruction of the Grand Concourse from 171st Street to 175th Street, which is already in planning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/314616942/Grand-Concourse-Reconstruction-Phase-3|title=GRAND CONCOURSE PHASE 3|date=June 1, 2016|website=[[Scribd]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> In January 2017, the [[New York City Department of Transportation]] started planning for a fourth phase, which will renovate the section between 175th Street and Fordham Road.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Gentrification ====\nBecause of its attractive art deco buildings and close proximity to [[Manhattan]], the southern portion has been experiencing [[gentrification]] and is drawing many [[Yuppie|young professionals]] to the area.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Berger|first1=Joseph|title=No Longer Burning, the South Bronx Gentrifies|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/26/nyregion/grand-concourse-neighborhood-in-the-south-bronx-gentrifies.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 25, 2015}}</ref> Since the 2000s, the area around the Grand Concourse has been the center of what real state agents are calling a \u201crenewal\", with new residents moving in, and severe crime rates having decreased significantly. ''The New York Times'' cited several residents who believed that, while the region would experience demographic changes, it would be working-class, \u201ccommunity-oriented\u201d people, as opposed to the richer individuals that have [[Gentrification|gentrified]] other neighborhoods of the city.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/30/realestate/the-grand-concourse-growing-signs-of-a-renewal.html|title=The Grand Concourse: Growing Signs of a Renewal|last=Hughes|first=C. J.|date=November 26, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Significant buildings ==\n[[File:Louis J Heintz Kilmer Pk jeh.jpg|thumb|upright|Louis J Heintz, promoter of Grand Concourse, in Kilmer Park<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/joyce-kilmer-park/monuments/701|title=Joyce Kilmer Park \u2013 NYC Parks|accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref>]]\nSeveral buildings of importance to New York City and the Bronx, both because of their history and their current use, are located along the Grand Concourse.<ref name=\"encnyc\" /> There are also numerous structures designated as [[New York City designated landmark|New York City Landmarks]] (NYCL) and [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP) on the Concourse.<ref name=\"nris\"/><ref>Interactive map: {{cite web|url=https://nyclpc.maps.arcgis.com/apps/webappviewer/index.html?id=93a88691cace4067828b1eede432022b|title=Discover New York City Landmarks |publisher=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission |via=[[ArcGIS]] |access-date= December 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NysNrhpNom\">{{cite web|url=https://cris.parks.ny.gov/|title=Cultural Resource Information System (CRIS)|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]|format=Searchable database|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20150701003048/http://cris.parks.ny.gov/|archive-date=July 1, 2015|accessdate=March 1, 2016}} ''Note:'' This includes {{cite web|url=https://cris.parks.ny.gov/Uploads/ViewDoc.aspx?mode=A&id=26710&q=false|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Grand Concourse Historic District|author=Merrill Hesch|date=May 1987|format=PDF|accessdate=March 1, 2016}} and [https://cris.parks.ny.gov/Uploads/ViewDoc.aspx?mode=A&id=26709&q=false ''Accompanying 14 photographs'']</ref> From south to north (in increasing address order), they include:\n\n* 475 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[Hostos Community College]]\n* 558 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[United States Post Office\u2013Bronx Central Annex|The Bronx General Post Office]] (NRHP, NYCL; built 1935-1937; architect [[Thomas Harlan Ellett]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/80002584.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: Bronx Central Annex-U.S. Post Office|date=May 6, 1980|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/0837.pdf|title=Bronx General Post Office|date=November 25, 1975|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref> The interior includes a notable series of [[New Deal]]-era murals in [[fresco]] created in 1939 by [[Ben Shahn]] and [[Bernarda Bryson Shahn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2552.pdf|title=Bronx General Post Office Lobby, First Floor Interior|date=December 17, 2013|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* 851 Grand Concourse \u2013 The [[Bronx County Courthouse]] (NRHP, NYCL; built 1931-1934; architect Joseph H. Freelander and Max Hausle)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/0928.pdf|title=Bronx County Building|date=July 13, 1976|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/05000748.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: Bronx County Courthouse|date=September 8, 1983|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* 1040 Grand Concourse \u2013 The [[Bronx Museum of the Arts]] (built 1961, converted to museum 1982, addition 2006)<ref name=\"NYCL p. 20\" />\n* 1125 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[Andrew Freedman Home]] (NYCL; built 1924; architect Friedlander Jacobs),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1796.pdf|title=Andrew Freedman Home|date=June 2, 1992|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref> later converted into a small hotel<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hu|first=Winnie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/19/nyregion/the-bronx-as-destination-new-hoteliers-hope-so.html|title=Can Bronx Be a Destination? The Hope Is for Nights at a Time|date=February 18, 2013|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 24, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* 1150 Grand Concourse \u2013 The Fish Building (built 1937)<ref name=\"Dolnick\">{{cite news|last=Dolnick|first=Sam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/23/nyregion/23concourse.html|title=As Concourse Regains Luster, City Notices|date=June 22, 2010|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref>\n* 2403 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[Paradise Theater (Bronx)|Loew's Paradise Theater]] (NYCL; built 1929)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1891.pdf|title=Loew's Paradise Theater|date=April 15, 1997|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2193.pdf|title=Loew's Paradise Theater Interior|date=May 16, 2006|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* 2516-2530 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[Dollar Savings Bank Building]] (NYCL; built 1932-33, 1937-38, and 1949-52; architect Adolf L. Muller of Halsey, McCormack & Helmer). The 10-story headquarters of the Dollar Dry Dock Savings Banks (now liquidated),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1889.pdf|title=Dollar Savings Bank|date=July 19, 1994|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1890.pdf|title=Dollar Savings Bank Interior|date=July 19, 1994|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref> it contains a clock tower at its top.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hu|first=Winnie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/31/nyregion/after-years-frozen-in-time-a-clock-above-the-bronx-may-tick-again.html|title=Plans to Fix a Bronx Landmark and a Hole in Time|date=December 30, 2013|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 24, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* 2640 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage|Poe Cottage]], the last home of [[Edgar Allan Poe]] (NRHP, NYCL; built 1812; architect John Wheeler)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/0110.pdf|title=Edgar Allan Poe Cottage|date=February 15, 1966|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/80002588.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: Edgar Allan Poe Cottage|date=August 19, 1980|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Grand Concourse Historic District ===\nIn 2011, the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] designated the Grand Concourse from 153rd to 167th Streets as part of the Grand Concourse Historic District.<ref name=\"Dolnick\" /><ref>[http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/25/the-grand-concourse-gets-its-due/ Grand Concourse Gets Its Due] by Patrick Wall, October 25, 2011, ''The New York Times''</ref> The State of New York had previously nominated the buildings at 730\u20131000, 1100\u20131520, 1560, and 851\u20131675 Grand Concourse for listing on the National Register of Historic Places as a historic district.<ref name=\"nris\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rosenblum|first=Constance|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/21/arts/design/21concourse.html|title=Grand, Wasn\u2019t It?|date=August 20, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 24, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\n==In popular culture==\n\n*The [[Fordham Road]]-Concourse area and Krum's soda fountain are featured in [[Avery Corman]]'s ''The Old Neighborhood'' novel.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Corman|first=Avery|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/11/20/magazine/grand-concourse-a-writer-s-return-what-s-happening-on-the-street-of-dreams.html|title=Grand Concourse: A Writer's Return; What's Happening on the Street of Dreams|date=November 20, 1988|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 24, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* In [[Jacob M. Appel]]'s story, \"The Grand Concourse\" (2007), a woman who grew up in the [[Lewis Morris]] Building returns to the [[Morrisania]] neighborhood with her adult daughter to discover the boulevard is far from how she remembers it.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The Grand Concourse|url=http://www.threepennyreview.com/tocs/109_sp07.html|journal=Threepenny Review|last=Appel|first=Jacob M.|date=Spring 2007|website=www.threepennyreview.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 24, 2020|issue=109}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]]\n* [[1100 Grand Concourse]]\n* [[Paradise Theater (Bronx)|Paradise Theater]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n\n* {{cite book|last=Gonzalez|first=Evelyn|title=The Bronx|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0-231-12115-6|publication-place=New York Chichester|oclc=71238523}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2403.pdf|title=Grand Concourse Historic District|last=|first=|date=October 25, 2011|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2011}}|dead-url=}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rosenblum|first=Constance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1XbUjZFIOtsC|title=Boulevard of Dreams: Heady Times, Heartbreak, and Hope along the Grand Concourse in the Bronx|publisher=NYU Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8147-7636-0|ref=harv|access-date=April 24, 2020}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Grand Concourse (Bronx)}}\n\n{{Bronx streets}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n[[Category:Art Deco architecture in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:New York City designated historic districts]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Streets in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Boulevard in the Bronx, New York}}\n{{Infobox street\n| name                    = Grand Concourse\n| marker_image            = \n| native_name             =\n| native_name_lang        =\n| alternate_name          =\n| image                   = 1650 Grand Concourse.jpg\n| image_size              = 300px\n| image_alt               =\n| image_map               = \n| caption                 = Looking southward from 179th Street with [[Manhattan]] in the background\n| map_type                =\n| map_size                = 300px\n| map_caption             = \n| map_alt                 = \n| other_name              =\n| former_names            = \n| part_of                 =\n| namesake                = \n| type                    =\n| owner                   = [[City of New York]]\n| maint                   = [[NYCDOT]]\n| length_mi               = 5.2\n| length_ref              = <ref name=google/>\n| length_notes            =\n| width                   =\n| area                    =\n| addresses               =\n| location                = [[Bronx]], [[New York City]]\n| postal_code             =\n| metro                   = \n| coordinates             = \n| direction_a             = South\n| terminus_a              = {{jct|state=NY|I|87|road=138th Street}} in [[Mott Haven, Bronx|Mott Haven]]\n| direction_b             = North\n| terminus_b              = {{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Mosholu}} in [[Bedford Park, Bronx|Bedford Park]]\n| junction                = \n| east                    =\n| west                    =\n| designer                = Louis Aloys Risse\n| main_contractor         = \n| cost                    =\n| references              =\n| commissioning_date      =\n| construction_start_date = {{Start date|1894}}\n| completion_date         = {{Start date|1909}}\n| inauguration_date       = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| demolition_date         =\n| known_for               =\n| status                  =\n| embedded =\n{{Infobox NRHP | name =Grand Concourse Historic District\n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type = hd  | nocat = yes\n  | image = Grand Concourse 2007-11.jpg\n  | caption = Art Deco apartment buildings along Grand Concourse\n  | location= [[The Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|49|50|N|73|55|15|W|region:US-NY_type:landmark_dim:10km|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = New York City\n  | area =\n| architect= Multiple\n| architecture= Late 19th and 20th Century Revivals, Art Deco, Other\n | added = August 24, 1987\n | governing_body = Local\n | refnum=87001388<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n  | designated_other2_name = NYC Landmark\n  | designated_other2_date = October 25, 2011\n  | designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n  | designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n  | designated_other2_number = 2403\n  | designated_other2_color = #ffe978\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Grand Concourse''' (also known as the '''Grand Boulevard and Concourse''') is a {{Convert|5.2|mi||-long|abbr=|adj=mid}} thoroughfare in the [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[the Bronx]] in [[New York City]]. Grand Concourse runs through several neighborhoods, including [[Bedford Park, Bronx|Bedford Park]], [[Concourse, Bronx|Concourse]], [[Highbridge, Bronx|Highbridge]], [[Fordham, Bronx|Fordham]], [[Mott Haven, Bronx|Mott Haven]], [[Norwood, Bronx|Norwood]] and [[Tremont, Bronx|Tremont]]. For most of its length, the Concourse is {{Convert|180|ft||abbr=}} wide.\n\nThe Grand Concourse was designed by Louis Aloys Risse, an immigrant from [[Saint-Avold]], [[Lorraine]], [[France]]. Risse first conceived of the road in 1890, and the Concourse was built between 1894 and 1909, with an additional extension in 1927. The development of the Concourse led to the construction of apartment buildings surrounding the boulevard, and by 1939 it was called \"the [[Park Avenue]] of middle-class Bronx residents\".<ref name=\"Moore 1981\" /> A period of decline followed in the 1960s and 1970s, when these residences became dilapidated and the Concourse was redesigned to be more motorist-friendly. Renovation and redevelopment started in the 1980s, and a portion of the Grand Concourse was reconstructed starting in the 2000s.\n\nThe southern portion of the Grand Concourse is surrounded by several historically important residential buildings, which were listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1987 as part of the '''Grand Concourse Historic District'''. In 2011, the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] designated numerous buildings around the Grand Concourse as part of a city landmark district. Additionally, several individual points of interest are located on or near the Concourse, including the [[Bronx Museum of the Arts]] and [[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]].\n\n== Description ==\nThe Grand Concourse's southern terminus is at 138th Street. Shortly afterward, it merges with the entrance ramp to southbound [[Major Deegan Expressway]] ([[Interstate 87 (New York)|I-87]]), as well as the exit ramp from northbound I-87. The Grand Concourse continues as a divided eight-lane avenue, with two to three traffic lanes in each direction, until 161st Street.<ref name=google/> North of there, the [[frontage road|service roads]] in each direction begin, and a unidirectional buffered [[bike lane]] runs on the left edge of either service road.<ref name=\"NYC Bike Map\">{{cite web | title=NYC DOT Bicycle Map 2018 | website=NYC.gov |publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]] |date=2018 | url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/bikemap-2018.pdf| access-date=October 17, 2018}}</ref> The Grand Concourse is briefly a ten-lane boulevard with four roadways, two in each direction, until just south of 165th Street. There, the northbound and southbound inner roadways merge into a five-lane undivided roadway with two lanes in each direction and a left-turn lane and painted median in the center.<ref name=google/> The buffered bike lanes on each service road end at 171st Street, and conventional bike lanes start on the right lane of the respective service roads.<ref name=\"NYC Bike Map\"/> This configuration with three roadways (two service roads and one main road) continues north until [[Mosholu Parkway]], where the Grand Concourse ends. At [[Fordham Road]], the main road passes underneath in a [[grade-separated junction]], while the service roads intersect with Fordham Road.<ref name=\"google\">{{google maps|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Grand+Concourse,+Bronx,+NY/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x89c2f46bc54b9a29:0xdb71eee2ad49db66?sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiQ7pn9uI3eAhWBl-AKHTmxCOMQ8gEwAHoECAAQAQ|title=Grand Concourse, Bronx, NY|access-date=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBetween approximately 161st and 204th Streets, the [[New York City Subway]]'s [[IND Concourse Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Concourse}}) runs under the Grand Concourse. The [[IRT Jerome Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Jerome south}}) also runs underneath the boulevard for a short section south of 149th Street.<ref name=google/> The [[Bx1 (New York City bus)|Bx1]] local bus and the [[BxM4 (New York City bus)|BxM4]] express bus run the entire length of the Grand Concourse, while the [[Bx2 (New York City bus)|Bx2]] local bus runs on the Concourse north of 149th Street.<ref>{{cite NYC bus map|Bx}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Construction ===\n[[File:The_Great_north_side,_or,_Borough_of_the_Bronx,_New_York_(1897)_(14765078865).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Intersection plan, 1892]]\nRisse first conceived of the road in 1890, as a means of connecting the borough of [[Manhattan]] to the northern Bronx.<ref>[http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/03/18/looking-back-at-the-grand-concourses-first-century/ ''The New York Times'', March 18, 2009] Looking back at the Grand Concourse First Century</ref> Construction began on the Grand Concourse in 1894 and it was opened to traffic in November 1909. Built during the height of the [[City Beautiful movement]], it was modeled on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in Paris but is considerably larger, stretching four miles (6&nbsp;km) in length, measuring {{convert|180|ft|m}} across, and separated into three roadways by tree-lined dividers, so some minor streets did not cross the Concourse. The cost of the project was $14 million (worth ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|14000000|1900}}}} today).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westegg.com/inflation/ |title=The Inflation Calculator |accessdate=April 13, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5QVXNUZmW?url=http://www.westegg.com/inflation/ |archivedate=July 21, 2007 }}</ref> \n\nThe Grand Concourse originally stretched from Bronx Borough Hall at 161st Street north to [[Van Cortlandt Park]]. It was expanded southward to 138th Street in 1927 after Mott Avenue was widened to accommodate the boulevard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forgotten-ny.com/2011/10/back-on-course-revisiting-the-grand-concourse|title=BACK ON \u2018COURSE: Revisiting the Grand Concourse|publisher=|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> Evidence of the Grand Concourse extension's old name is present at the [[149th Street\u2013Grand Concourse station]], where there are signs reading \"Mott Avenue\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Development ===\nThe [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]]'s Jerome Avenue Line opened a few blocks west of the Grand Concourse in 1917, initiating a housing boom amongst upwardly mobile, predominantly Jewish and Italian, families who were fleeing the crowded tenements of Manhattan. In 1923, [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|Yankee Stadium]] opened near the Grand Concourse at 161st Street, down the hill from the [[Concourse Plaza Hotel]]. South of Fordham Road, the palatial [[Paradise Theater (Bronx)|Loew's Paradise]] theater, one of the [[Loew's Wonder Theatres]] and at one time the largest movie theater in New York City, was constructed in 1929.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fire Badly Damages Paradise Theater, a Bronx Landmark|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/06/nyregion/fire-damages-paradise-theater-a-bronx-landmark.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDevelopment of the Concourse was further encouraged by the opening of the [[Independent Subway System]]'s Concourse Line in 1933. By the mid-1930s, almost three hundred apartment buildings had been built along the Concourse. Customarily five or six stories high with wide entrance courtyards bordered with grass and shrubs, among these apartments are many of the finest examples of [[Art Deco]] and [[Art Moderne]] architecture in the United States. Even though the [[Great Depression in the United States|Great Depression]], which was happening at the time, ended the period of tremendous growth, privately financed apartment buildings continued to be constructed. Furthermore, work was done on the Grand Concourse as part of WPA programs.<ref name=\"encnyc\">{{cite enc-nyc2}}</ref> During this period, the Bronx had more amenities than other boroughs: in 1934, almost 99% of residences had private bathrooms, and 95% had central heating.<ref>{{cite web|title=ONE HUNDRED YEARS OF THE BRONX |url=http://www.bronxhistoricalsociety.org/journal/historyofthebronxjournal.html |accessdate=October 11, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021042529/http://www.bronxhistoricalsociety.org/journal/historyofthebronxjournal.html |archivedate=October 21, 2007 }}</ref> In the 1939 [[American Guide Series|''WPA Guide to New York City'']], the Grand Concourse was described as \"the [[Park Avenue]] of middle-class Bronx residents, and the lease to an apartment in one of its many large buildings is considered evidence of at least moderate business success.\"<ref name=\"Moore 1981\">{{cite book|last=Moore|first=D.D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=POfJa1DJz9oC&pg=PA76|title=At Home in America: Second Generation New York Jews|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=1981|isbn=978-0-231-05063-0|series=Columbia history of urban life|page=76|access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite fednyc|page=517}}</ref>\n\n=== Decline ===\nIn 1941, the New York City Planning Department proposed converting the boulevard into an expressway, in order to connect the [[Major Deegan Expressway]] and the proposed Park Avenue Expressway to the south with the [[Mosholu Parkway]] to the north. However, these plans were abandoned following the southern extension of the [[Bronx River Parkway]] in the 1940s and the extension of the Major Deegan Expressway to the north in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycroads.com/roads/grand-concourse/|title=Grand Concourse Express Highway (NY 22 and NY 100, unbuilt)|publisher=|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe south and central Bronx rapidly deteriorated in the 1960s, as there was general disinvestment in the region's real estate, exacerbated by [[urban renewal]] and [[redlining]] programs.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 18\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2011|ps=.|p=18}}</ref><ref name=\"Gonzalez p. 111\">{{harvnb|Gonzalez|2006|ps=.|p=111}}</ref> Many white residents of the South Bronx left for suburban areas in a process known as [[white flight]]; they were helped by the construction of the [[Interstate Highway System]].<ref name=\"Gonzalez p. 148\">{{harvnb|Gonzalez|2006|ps=.|p=148}}</ref><ref name=\"Rosenblum p. 179\">{{harvnb|Rosenblum|2009|ps=.|p=179}}</ref> At the same time, [[African Americans]] and [[Stateside Puerto Ricans|Puerto Ricans]] were moving to the Bronx for blue-collar jobs; however, these jobs were increasingly being shifted to the suburbs, the [[Southern United States]], and other countries.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 18\" /><ref name=\"Rosenblum p. 179\" /> Racial discrimination against these demographic groups prevented them from moving to the suburbs, forcing them into deteriorating urban housing stock.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 18\" /><ref name=\"Rosenblum p. 109\">{{harvnb|Rosenblum|2009|ps=.|p=109}}</ref> The buildings around the Concourse thus came to be perceived as old and low-rent, and subsequent cycles of disinvestment led landlords on the Concourse to pay decreasingly less attention to their housing stock,<ref name=\"Gonzalez p. 148\" /> while banks and insurance companies failed to give financial support to these neighborhoods.<ref name=\"Gonzalez p. 181\">{{harvnb|Gonzalez|2006|ps=.|p=181}}</ref> Further outward migration between 1968 and 1970 drained the areas along the Grand Concourse of most of its remaining middle-class residents. Many buildings in the area were damaged by arson, vandalism, and a lack of maintenance.\n\nThe road itself was modified to be more hospitable to motorists.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 21\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2011|ps=.|p=21}}</ref> During the 1960s, the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] removed the grass median on the Concourse and replaced it with cement that was painted green.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Williams|first=Timothy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/09/nyregion/a-resurgence-in-the-bronx-is-finally-putting-the-grand-back-in-the.html|title=A Resurgence in the Bronx Is Finally Putting the Grand Back in the Concourse|date=2006-05-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By the 1980s, ''The New York Times'' characterized the Concourse as \"a driver\u2019s paradise\". Traffic lights were timed so that motorists received a \"[[green wave]]\", moving through intersections at a time. Meanwhile, pedestrian crossings and trees were eliminated, and green highway signs were placed on the Concourse.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Kugel|first=Seth|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/16/nyregion/neighborhood-report-grand-concourse-making-once-noble-boulevard-look-less-like.html|title=NEIGHBORHOOD REPORT: GRAND CONCOURSE; Making a Once-Noble Boulevard Look Less Like the Interstate...|date=2004-05-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Restoration ===\nDuring the 1980s, landlords along the Concourse and elsewhere in the South Bronx began rehabilitating their buildings.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 20\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2011|ps=.|p=20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Goodman|first=George W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/12/realestate/rehabilitation-holding-bronx-blight-at-bay.html|title=Rehabilitation Holding Bronx Blight at Bay|date=1983-06-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[Bronx Museum of the Arts]], was one of the institutions to move to the area, relocating in 1982 to a former synagogue at Grand Concourse and 167th Street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 20\" /> The city created the \"Special Grand Concourse Preservation District\" in 1989 to preserve the character of residential buildings on the Concourse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zr.planning.nyc.gov/index.php/article-xii/chapter-2|title=Chapter 2 {{!}} Zoning Resolution: Special Grand Concourse Preservation District|last=|first=|date=1989-09-28|website=zr.planning.nyc.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> This led to new building developments on the Concourse starting in the 1990s,<ref name=\"Rosenblum p. 221\">{{harvnb|Rosenblum|2009|ps=.|p=221}}</ref> including the [[Rafael Vi\u00f1oly]]-designed Bronx Housing Courthouse at 1118 Grand Concourse.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 20\" /> In addition, basement stores started opening on the Concourse in the 1980s, serving the predominantly minority communities around the boulevard. By 2003, a ''New York Times'' writer observed that \"every block between 161st Street and 196th Street now has a grocery, a barber shop, a travel agency or a medical clinic\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Berger|first=Joseph|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/18/nyregion/concourse-gets-used-commerce-street-s-historic-character-clashes-with-modernity.html|title=Concourse Gets Used To Commerce; Street's Historic Character Clashes With Modernity|date=2003-09-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Boulevard reconstruction ====\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1 = Grand Conc 165 jeh.JPG\n| caption1 = Renovated intersection with [[161st Street (Bronx)|161st Street]] in 2008\n| image2 = GC under Fordham Road jeh.JPG\n| caption2 = Unrenovated section at East 187th Street\n| total_width = 400\n| alt1 = \n}}\n\nBy the early 1990s, politicians and community advocates strove to make the Concourse more usable for pedestrians. At that time, the Concourse was one of the most dangerous streets in New York City, with twelve pedestrians dying in 1991, rivaling the reputation of [[Queens Boulevard]] as the \"Boulevard of Death\".<ref name=\":4\" /> In 1992, the [[New York City Department of Transportation]] (NYCDOT) conducted a study of the Grand Concourse, which resulted in improvements such as left-turn signals; pedestrian barriers; roadway markings; repainted crosswalks; and new and improved signage. These improvements continued along the entire corridor through 2006.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/safetyrpt07_1.pdf|title=SAFE STREETS NYC: The Bronx|last=|first=|date=June 2007|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|pages=16\u201330|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref>{{Rp|16\u201319}} As an experiment, the NYCDOT also completely rebuilt the section between [[161st Street (Bronx)|161st Street]] and 167th Streets starting in 1999, as a \"demonstration\" project.<ref name=\":3\" />{{rp|20\u201326}} The Grand Concourse underwent an $18 million restoration and landscaping to widen and landscape the medians; improve lighting; add new signage; build pedestrian planters in the medians; and add bike lanes. This resulted in a 69% drop in accidents along this section between 1998 and 2005.<ref name=\":3\" />{{rp|20\u201322}} The final part of the demonstration project was completed in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/161_166grandconcourse.pdf|title=Grand Concourse 2008|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the success of the \"demonstration\" reconstruction, the NYCDOT unveiled a four-phase capital project between 161st Street and [[Fordham Road]] as part of a capital project, which would receive funding directly from the city. Tthe demonstration project was the first phase of the capital project. A reconstruction of the Grand Concourse between 166th and 171st Street began in 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/2013-02-grand-concourse.pdf|title=HWXP136A RECONSTRUCTION OF GRAND CONCOURSE SERVICE ROADS EAST 166TH STREET TO EAST 171ST STREET|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]] |date=February 2013|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> and was finished in June 2017.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/grand-concourse-jan2017.pdf|title=GRAND CONCOURSE PHASE 4 Community Workshop|last=|first=|date=January 19, 2017|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|access-date=March 6, 2017}}</ref> Funding is being allocated for a reconstruction of the Grand Concourse from 171st Street to 175th Street, which is already in planning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/314616942/Grand-Concourse-Reconstruction-Phase-3|title=GRAND CONCOURSE PHASE 3|date=June 1, 2016|website=[[Scribd]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Transportation]]|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> In January 2017, the [[New York City Department of Transportation]] started planning for a fourth phase, which will renovate the section between 175th Street and Fordham Road.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Gentrification ====\nBecause of its attractive art deco buildings and close proximity to [[Manhattan]], the southern portion has been experiencing [[gentrification]] and is drawing many [[Yuppie|young professionals]] to the area.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Berger|first1=Joseph|title=No Longer Burning, the South Bronx Gentrifies|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/26/nyregion/grand-concourse-neighborhood-in-the-south-bronx-gentrifies.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 25, 2015}}</ref> Since the 2000s, the area around the Grand Concourse has been the center of what real state agents are calling a \u201crenewal\", with new residents moving in, and severe crime rates having decreased significantly. ''The New York Times'' cited several residents who believed that, while the region would experience demographic changes, it would be working-class, \u201ccommunity-oriented\u201d people, as opposed to the richer individuals that have [[Gentrification|gentrified]] other neighborhoods of the city.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/30/realestate/the-grand-concourse-growing-signs-of-a-renewal.html|title=The Grand Concourse: Growing Signs of a Renewal|last=Hughes|first=C. J.|date=November 26, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Significant buildings ==\n[[File:Louis J Heintz Kilmer Pk jeh.jpg|thumb|upright|Louis J Heintz, promoter of Grand Concourse, in Kilmer Park<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/joyce-kilmer-park/monuments/701|title=Joyce Kilmer Park \u2013 NYC Parks|accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref>]]\nSeveral buildings of importance to New York City and the Bronx, both because of their history and their current use, are located along the Grand Concourse.<ref name=\"encnyc\" /> There are also numerous structures designated as [[New York City designated landmark|New York City Landmarks]] (NYCL) and [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP) on the Concourse.<ref name=\"nris\"/><ref>Interactive map: {{cite web|url=https://nyclpc.maps.arcgis.com/apps/webappviewer/index.html?id=93a88691cace4067828b1eede432022b|title=Discover New York City Landmarks |publisher=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission |via=[[ArcGIS]] |access-date= December 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NysNrhpNom\">{{cite web|url=https://cris.parks.ny.gov/|title=Cultural Resource Information System (CRIS)|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]|format=Searchable database|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20150701003048/http://cris.parks.ny.gov/|archive-date=July 1, 2015|accessdate=March 1, 2016}} ''Note:'' This includes {{cite web|url=https://cris.parks.ny.gov/Uploads/ViewDoc.aspx?mode=A&id=26710&q=false|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Grand Concourse Historic District|author=Merrill Hesch|date=May 1987|format=PDF|accessdate=March 1, 2016}} and [https://cris.parks.ny.gov/Uploads/ViewDoc.aspx?mode=A&id=26709&q=false ''Accompanying 14 photographs'']</ref> From south to north (in increasing address order), they include:\n\n* 475 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[Hostos Community College]]\n* 558 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[United States Post Office\u2013Bronx Central Annex|The Bronx General Post Office]] (NRHP, NYCL; built 1935-1937; architect [[Thomas Harlan Ellett]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/80002584.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: Bronx Central Annex-U.S. Post Office|date=May 6, 1980|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/0837.pdf|title=Bronx General Post Office|date=November 25, 1975|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref> The interior includes a notable series of [[New Deal]]-era murals in [[fresco]] created in 1939 by [[Ben Shahn]] and [[Bernarda Bryson Shahn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2552.pdf|title=Bronx General Post Office Lobby, First Floor Interior|date=December 17, 2013|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* 851 Grand Concourse \u2013 The [[Bronx County Courthouse]] (NRHP, NYCL; built 1931-1934; architect Joseph H. Freelander and Max Hausle)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/0928.pdf|title=Bronx County Building|date=July 13, 1976|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/05000748.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: Bronx County Courthouse|date=September 8, 1983|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* 1040 Grand Concourse \u2013 The [[Bronx Museum of the Arts]] (built 1961, converted to museum 1982, addition 2006)<ref name=\"NYCL p. 20\" />\n* 1125 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[Andrew Freedman Home]] (NYCL; built 1924; architect Friedlander Jacobs),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1796.pdf|title=Andrew Freedman Home|date=June 2, 1992|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref> later converted into a small hotel<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hu|first=Winnie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/19/nyregion/the-bronx-as-destination-new-hoteliers-hope-so.html|title=Can Bronx Be a Destination? The Hope Is for Nights at a Time|date=2013-02-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* 1150 Grand Concourse \u2013 The Fish Building (built 1937)<ref name=\"Dolnick\">{{cite news|last=Dolnick|first=Sam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/23/nyregion/23concourse.html|title=As Concourse Regains Luster, City Notices|date=June 22, 2010|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref>\n* 2403 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[Paradise Theater (Bronx)|Loew's Paradise Theater]] (NYCL; built 1929)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1891.pdf|title=Loew's Paradise Theater|date=April 15, 1997|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2193.pdf|title=Loew's Paradise Theater Interior|date=May 16, 2006|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* 2516-2530 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[Dollar Savings Bank Building]] (NYCL; built 1932-33, 1937-38, and 1949-52; architect Adolf L. Muller of Halsey, McCormack & Helmer). The 10-story headquarters of the Dollar Dry Dock Savings Banks (now liquidated),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1889.pdf|title=Dollar Savings Bank|date=July 19, 1994|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1890.pdf|title=Dollar Savings Bank Interior|date=July 19, 1994|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref> it contains a clock tower at its top.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hu|first=Winnie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/31/nyregion/after-years-frozen-in-time-a-clock-above-the-bronx-may-tick-again.html|title=Plans to Fix a Bronx Landmark and a Hole in Time|date=2013-12-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* 2640 Grand Concourse \u2013 [[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage|Poe Cottage]], the last home of [[Edgar Allan Poe]] (NRHP, NYCL; built 1812; architect John Wheeler)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/0110.pdf|title=Edgar Allan Poe Cottage|date=February 15, 1966|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/80002588.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: Edgar Allan Poe Cottage|date=August 19, 1980|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Grand Concourse Historic District ===\nIn 2011, the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] designated the Grand Concourse from 153rd to 167th Streets as part of the Grand Concourse Historic District.<ref name=\"Dolnick\" /><ref>[http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/25/the-grand-concourse-gets-its-due/ Grand Concourse Gets Its Due] by Patrick Wall, October 25, 2011, ''The New York Times''</ref> The State of New York had previously nominated the buildings at 730\u20131000, 1100\u20131520, 1560, and 851\u20131675 Grand Concourse for listing on the National Register of Historic Places as a historic district.<ref name=\"nris\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rosenblum|first=Constance|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/21/arts/design/21concourse.html|title=Grand, Wasn\u2019t It?|date=2009-08-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\n==In popular culture==\n\n*The [[Fordham Road]]-Concourse area and Krum's soda fountain are featured in [[Avery Corman]]'s ''The Old Neighborhood'' novel.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Corman|first=Avery|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/11/20/magazine/grand-concourse-a-writer-s-return-what-s-happening-on-the-street-of-dreams.html|title=Grand Concourse: A Writer's Return; What's Happening on the Street of Dreams|date=1988-11-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-24|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* In [[Jacob M. Appel]]'s story, \"The Grand Concourse\" (2007), a woman who grew up in the [[Lewis Morris]] Building returns to the [[Morrisania]] neighborhood with her adult daughter to discover the boulevard is far from how she remembers it.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The Grand Concourse|url=http://www.threepennyreview.com/tocs/109_sp07.html|journal=Threepenny Review|last=Appel|first=Jacob M.|date=Spring 2007|website=www.threepennyreview.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24|issue=109}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]]\n* [[1100 Grand Concourse]]\n* [[Paradise Theater (Bronx)|Paradise Theater]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n\n* {{cite book|last=Gonzalez|first=Evelyn|title=The Bronx|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0-231-12115-6|publication-place=New York Chichester|oclc=71238523}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2403.pdf|title=Grand Concourse Historic District|last=|first=|date=October 25, 2011|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2011}}|dead-url=}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rosenblum|first=Constance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1XbUjZFIOtsC|title=Boulevard of Dreams: Heady Times, Heartbreak, and Hope along the Grand Concourse in the Bronx|publisher=NYU Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8147-7636-0|ref=harv|access-date=April 24, 2020}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Grand Concourse (Bronx)}}\n\n{{Bronx streets}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n[[Category:Art Deco architecture in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:New York City designated historic districts]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Streets in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration in New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grand_Concourse_(Bronx)"}
{"title_page": "Kosmos 4", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name          = Kosmos 4\n| image         = \n| image_caption = \n\n| mission_type        = Optical imaging reconnaissance\n| operator            = \n| Harvard_designation = 1962 Xi 1\n| COSPAR_ID           = 1962-014A\n| SATCAT              = 00287\n| mission_duration    = 3 days (4 days planned)\n\n| spacecraft_type   = [[Zenit (satellite)|Zenit-2]]\n| manufacturer      = [[OKB-1]]\n| launch_mass       = 4610 kg <ref name=\"Display\"/>\n\n| launch_date       = 26 April 1962, 10:02 [[GMT]]\n| launch_rocket     = [[Vostok-K]]\n| launch_site       = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Gagarin's Start|Site 1/5]]\n| launch_contractor = [[OKB-1]]\n\n| disposal_type     = Recovered\n| landing_date      = 29 April 1962\n| landing_site      = Steppe of the [[Kazakhstan]]\n\n| orbit_epoch       = 26 April 1962\n| orbit_reference   = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] <ref name=\"Trajectory\"/>\n| orbit_regime      = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis   = 285 km\n| orbit_apoapsis    = 317 km\n| orbit_inclination = 65.0\u00b0\n| orbit_period      = 90.6 minutes\n| apsis             = gee\n}}\n\n'''Kosmos 4''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441 4}} meaning ''Cosmos 4''), also known as '''Zenit-2 No.2''' and occasionally in the West as '''Sputnik 14''' was the first [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[reconnaissance satellite]] to successfully reach orbit.\n\n==Spacecraft==\nKosmos 4 was a [[Zenit (satellite)|Zenit-2]] satellite, a first generation, low resolution reconnaissance satellite derived from the [[Vostok (spacecraft)|Vostok spacecraft]] used for [[human spaceflight|crewed]] flights.<ref name=\"Display\"/> It was the fourth satellite to be designated under the [[Kosmos (satellite)|Kosmos]] system, and the second Soviet attempt to launch a reconnaissance satellite, the previous attempt having failed after one of the [[Launch vehicle|carrier rockets]]' engines shut down prematurely.<ref name=\"EA-Zenit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/zenit2.htm |title=Zenit-2|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=2009-05-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6753VGwt2?url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/zenit2.htm |archivedate=2012-04-21}}</ref> It had a mass of {{convert|4610|kg}}.<ref name=\"Display\"/>\n\n==Mission==\nIt was launched on a [[Vostok-K]] rocket, which was making its seventh flight.<ref name=\"JSR-LL\">{{cite web|url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/launchlog.txt|title=Launch Log|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan |publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=2009-05-23}}</ref> It was the last Zenit launch to use the Vostok-K, before launches switched to the [[Vostok-2 (rocket)|Vostok-2]] starting with the next launch attempt in June 1962. The launch was conducted from [[Gagarin's Start|Site 1/5]] at the [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]], and occurred at 10:02:00 [[GMT]] on 26 April 1962.<ref name=\"EA-Soyuz\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/soyuz.htm|title=Soyuz|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=2009-05-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mqiUXlX2?url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/soyuz.htm|archivedate=2010-01-17}}</ref> Kosmos 4 was placed into a [[low Earth orbit]] with a [[apsis|perigee]] of {{convert|285|km}}, an [[apsis|apogee]] of {{convert|317|km}}, an [[Orbital inclination|inclination]] of 65.0\u00b0, and an [[orbital period]] of 90.6 minutes.<ref name=\"Trajectory\">{{Cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/displayTrajectory.action?id=1962-014A|title=Cosmos 4: Trajectory 1962-014A|date=27 February 2020|website=nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov|publisher=NASA|access-date=23 April 2020}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nIt conducted a four-day mission, to measure radiation before and after the US nuclear tests conducted during project [[Starfish Prime]].<ref name=\"Display\">{{Cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1962-014A|title=Cosmos 4: Display 1962-014A|date=27 February 2020|website=nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov|publisher=NASA|access-date=23 April 2020}} {{PD-notice}}</ref> However, leaks from the oxygen system tanks used for the orientation system resulted in the premature return of the spacecraft after three days of flight. During most of the flight the spacecraft was uncontrollable, before being deorbited and landing by [[parachute]] on 29 April 1962, and recovered by the Soviet forces in the steppe of the [[Kazakhstan]].<ref name=\"satcat\">{{cite web |url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/satcat.txt|title=Satellite Catalog|first=Jonathan|last=McDowell|work=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe next Zenit launch attempt, scheduled for May but delayed to 1 June 1962, failed to reach orbit, but the next launch successfully reached orbit as [[Kosmos 7]].<ref name=\"EA-Zenit\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* [[1962 in spaceflight]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Zenit-2 satellites}}\n{{Orbital launches in 1962}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kosmos 0004}}\n\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 1962]]\n[[Category:1962 in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Kosmos satellites]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 1962]]\n\n{{USSR-spacecraft-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name          = Kosmos 4\n| image         = \n| image_caption = \n\n| mission_type        = Optical imaging reconnaissance\n| operator            = \n| Harvard_designation = 1962 Xi 1\n| COSPAR_ID           = 1962-014A\n| SATCAT              = 00287\n| mission_duration    = 3 days (4 days planned)\n\n| spacecraft_type   = [[Zenit (satellite)|Zenit-2]]\n| manufacturer      = [[OKB-1]]\n| launch_mass       = 4610 kg <ref name=\"Display\"/>\n\n| launch_date       = 26 April 1962, 10:02 [[GMT]]\n| launch_rocket     = [[Vostok-K]]\n| launch_site       = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Gagarin's Start|Site 1/5]]\n| launch_contractor = [[OKB-1]]\n\n| disposal_type     = Recovered\n| landing_date      = 29 April 1962\n| landing_site      = Steppe of [[Kazakhstan]]\n\n| orbit_epoch       = 26 April 1962\n| orbit_reference   = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] <ref name=\"Trajectory\"/>\n| orbit_regime      = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis   = 285 km\n| orbit_apoapsis    = 317 km\n| orbit_inclination = 65.0\u00b0\n| orbit_period      = 90.6 minutes\n| apsis             = gee\n}}\n\n'''Kosmos 4''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441 4}} meaning ''Cosmos 4''), also known as '''Zenit-2 No.2''' and occasionally in the West as '''Sputnik 14''' was the first [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[reconnaissance satellite]] to successfully reach orbit.\n\n==Spacecraft==\nKosmos 4 was a [[Zenit (satellite)|Zenit-2]] satellite, a first generation, low resolution reconnaissance satellite derived from the [[Vostok (spacecraft)|Vostok spacecraft]] used for [[human spaceflight|crewed]] flights.<ref name=\"Display\"/> It was the fourth satellite to be designated under the [[Kosmos (satellite)|Kosmos]] system, and the second Soviet attempt to launch a reconnaissance satellite, the previous attempt having failed after one of the [[Launch vehicle|carrier rockets]]' engines shut down prematurely.<ref name=\"EA-Zenit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/zenit2.htm |title=Zenit-2|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=2009-05-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6753VGwt2?url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/zenit2.htm |archivedate=2012-04-21}}</ref> It had a mass of {{convert|4610|kg}}.<ref name=\"Display\"/>\n\n==Mission==\nIt was launched on a [[Vostok-K]] rocket, which was making its seventh flight.<ref name=\"JSR-LL\">{{cite web|url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/launchlog.txt|title=Launch Log|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan |publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=2009-05-23}}</ref> It was the last Zenit launch to use the Vostok-K, before launches switched to the [[Vostok-2 (rocket)|Vostok-2]] starting with the next launch attempt in June 1962. The launch was conducted from [[Gagarin's Start|Site 1/5]] at the [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]], and occurred at 10:02:00 [[GMT]] on 26 April 1962.<ref name=\"EA-Soyuz\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/soyuz.htm|title=Soyuz|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=2009-05-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mqiUXlX2?url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/soyuz.htm|archivedate=2010-01-17}}</ref> Kosmos 4 was placed into a [[low Earth orbit]] with a [[apsis|perigee]] of {{convert|285|km}}, an [[apsis|apogee]] of {{convert|317|km}}, an [[Orbital inclination|inclination]] of 65.0\u00b0, and an [[orbital period]] of 90.6 minutes.<ref name=\"Trajectory\">{{Cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/displayTrajectory.action?id=1962-014A|title=Cosmos 4: Trajectory 1962-014A|date=27 February 2020|website=nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov|publisher=NASA|access-date=23 April 2020}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nIt conducted a four-day mission, to measure radiation before and after the US nuclear tests conducted during project [[Starfish Prime]].<ref name=\"Display\">{{Cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1962-014A|title=Cosmos 4: Display 1962-014A|date=27 February 2020|website=nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov|publisher=NASA|access-date=23 April 2020}} {{PD-notice}}</ref> However, leaks from the oxygen system tanks used for the orientation system resulted in the premature return of the spacecraft after three days of flight. During most of the flight the spacecraft was uncontrollable, before being deorbited and landing by [[parachute]] on 29 April 1962, and recovered by the Soviet forces in the steppe of [[Kazakhstan]].<ref name=\"satcat\">{{cite web |url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/satcat.txt|title=Satellite Catalog|first=Jonathan|last=McDowell|work=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe next Zenit launch attempt, scheduled for May but delayed to 1 June 1962, failed to reach orbit, but the next launch successfully reached orbit as [[Kosmos 7]].<ref name=\"EA-Zenit\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* [[1962 in spaceflight]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Zenit-2 satellites}}\n{{Orbital launches in 1962}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kosmos 0004}}\n\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 1962]]\n[[Category:1962 in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Kosmos satellites]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 1962]]\n\n{{USSR-spacecraft-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CRS-20", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kosmos_4"}
{"title_page": "POZ (magazine)", "text_new": "{{Infobox magazine\n|title              = POZ\n|image_file         = PozMagCoverJanFeb2013.jpg\n|image_size         = 225px\n|image_caption      = ''POZ'' #185, January/February 2013 cover featuring [[AIDS education|AIDS educators]] Nathaniel and Linda Scruggs\n|editor             = Oriol R. Gutierrez Jr.\n|editor_title       = [[Editor-in-chief]]\n|previous_editor    = Sean O'Brien Strub (Founder and Advisory Editor), Regan Hofmann\n|staff_writer       = \n|based              = [[New York City]], New York\n|frequency          = 8x a year\n|circulation        = 125,000 {{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n|category           = [[News magazine]]\n|company            = Smart + Strong\n|publisher          = Susan Levey (Vice President, Sales/Publisher)\n|founded            = 1994\n|country            = United States\n|language           = [[English language|English]]\n|website            = {{URL|http://poz.com}}\n|issn               = 1075-5705\n}}\n\n'''''POZ''''' is a magazine that chronicles the lives of people affected by [[HIV/AIDS]].<ref name=\"Cassidy2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Cassidy|first1=William P.|title=Accent on the POZitive? AIDS Coverage in POZ, A Magazine for HIV-Positive Individuals|journal=Atlantic Journal of Communication|volume=13|issue=3|year=2005|pages=169\u2013182|issn=1545-6870|doi=10.1207/s15456889ajc1303_3}}</ref> Its website, POZ.com, has daily HIV/AIDS news, treatment information, forums, blogs, and personals.\n\n==History and profile==\nThe magazine was founded in 1994<ref>Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation,[http://www.glaad.org/media/AIDS/timeline/index.php \u201cTimeline of Major Media and Cultural Events in HIV and AIDS History \u2013 1994\u201d]</ref> by [[Sean Strub]], an HIV-positive and openly gay businessman and activist. Before launching ''POZ'', Strub was involved with numerous social issues, including [[politics]], [[environmentalism]], [[civil rights]], [[LGBT]] rights, and HIV/AIDS. He is now executive director of the Sero Project, which focuses on ending inappropriate criminal prosecutions of people with HIV.<ref>Sero Project's Site, [http://seroproject.com/what-we-do/ \"What We Do\"]</ref>\n\n''POZ'' is published by Smart + Strong, which also publishes ''AIDSmeds.com'', a website for HIV/AIDS treatment information; ''Real Health'', a magazine and website for [[African-American]] health; ''Tu Salud'', a magazine and website for [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] health; ''Sane'', a website for mental wellness; ''Hep'', a website for hepatitis information, and ''Cancer Health'', a website for cancer information.\n\nIn 2004, Strub sold Smart + Strong to CDM Publishing, LLC.<ref>POZ.com, [http://www.poz.com/staffbios.shtml POZ Staff Bios]</ref> Jeremy Grayzel is CEO of CDM Publishing and Smart + Strong. He was president of VNU eMedia (now known as Nielsen Business Media). Ian Anderson is president of Smart + Strong. He was director of product development at VNU eMedia. Diane Anderson is vice president of integrated sales. She joined ''POZ'' in 2018.\n\nIn 2006, Regan Hofmann <ref>Miller, Lia; \n[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/13/business/media/13poz.html?_r=1&scp=4&sq=poz&st=cse&oref=slogin \u201cA Poz Columnist is Named Its Editor\u201d]; The New York Times; March 13, 2006</ref> became editor-in-chief of ''POZ''. She was the writer of the magazine's \u201cAnonymous\u201d column. Previously, Hofmann was editor-in-chief of ''New Jersey Life'' and founded ''Poets, Artists & Madmen''. She is now a consultant focused on strategy, communications and change in the field of global health.<ref>Regan Hofmann's Site, [http://www.reganhofmann.com/about \"About Regan\"]</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Oriol R. Gutierrez Jr.<ref>POZ.com, [http://www.poz.com/articles/oriol_gutierrez_poz_457_22836.shtml \"Oriol Gutierrez Named Editor-in-Chief of POZ\"]</ref> became editor-in-chief of ''POZ''. He was deputy editor since 2008. Previously, Gutierrez was managing editor of ''DiversityInc'', as well as cofounder, publisher and editor-in-chief of ''LGNY Latino''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n* [http://www.aidsmeds.com AIDSmeds.com]\n* [http://www.realhealthmag.com RealHealthMag.com]\n* [http://www.tusaludmag.com TuSaludMag.com]\n* [http://www.sanemag.com SaneMag.com]\n* [http://www.hepmag.com HepMag.com]\n* [http://www.cancerhealth.com CancerHealth.com]\n* [http://www.smartandstrong.com SmartAndStrong.com]\n\n[[Category:American news magazines]]\n[[Category:American eight times annually magazines]]\n[[Category:Health magazines]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in the United States]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Media portrayal of HIV/AIDS]]\n[[Category:American lifestyle magazines]]\n\n\n{{health-mag-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox magazine\n|title              = POZ\n|image_file         = PozMagCoverJanFeb2013.jpg\n|image_size         = 225px\n|image_caption      = ''POZ'' #185, January/February 2013 cover featuring [[AIDS education|AIDS educators]] Nathaniel and Linda Scruggs\n|editor             = Oriol R. Gutierrez Jr.\n|editor_title       = [[Editor-in-chief]]\n|previous_editor    = Sean O'Brien Strub (Founder and Advisory Editor), Regan Hofmann\n|staff_writer       = \n|based              = [[New York City]], New York\n|frequency          = 8x a year\n|circulation        = 125,000 {{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n|category           = [[News magazine]]\n|company            = Smart + Strong\n|publisher          = Susan Levey (Vice President, Sales/Publisher)\n|founded            = 1994\n|country            = United States\n|language           = [[English language|English]]\n|website            = {{URL|http://poz.com}}\n|issn               = 1075-5705\n}}\n\n'''''POZ''''' is a magazine that chronicles the lives of people affected by [[HIV/AIDS]].<ref name=\"Cassidy2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Cassidy|first1=William P.|title=Accent on the POZitive? AIDS Coverage in POZ, A Magazine for HIV-Positive Individuals|journal=Atlantic Journal of Communication|volume=13|issue=3|year=2005|pages=169\u2013182|issn=1545-6870|doi=10.1207/s15456889ajc1303_3}}</ref> Its website, POZ.com, has daily HIV/AIDS news, treatment information, forums, blogs, and personals.\n\n==History and profile==\nThe magazine was founded in 1994<ref>Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation,[http://www.glaad.org/media/AIDS/timeline/index.php \u201cTimeline of Major Media and Cultural Events in HIV and AIDS History \u2013 1994\u201d]</ref> by [[Sean Strub]], an HIV-positive and openly gay businessman and activist. Before launching ''POZ'', Strub was involved with numerous social issues, including [[politics]], [[environmentalism]], [[civil rights]], [[LGBT]] rights, and HIV/AIDS. He is now executive director of the Sero Project, which focuses on ending inappropriate criminal prosecutions of people with HIV.<ref>Sero Project's Site, [http://seroproject.com/what-we-do/ \"What We Do\"]</ref>\n\n''POZ'' is published by Smart + Strong, which also publishes ''AIDSmeds.com'', a website for HIV/AIDS treatment information; ''Real Health'', a magazine and website for [[African-American]] health; ''Tu Salud'', a magazine and website for [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] health; ''Sane'', a website for mental wellness; ''Hep'', a website for hepatitis information, and ''Cancer Health'', a website for cancer information.\n\nIn 2004, Strub sold Smart + Strong to CDM Publishing, LLC.<ref>POZ.com, [http://www.poz.com/staffbios.shtml POZ Staff Bios]</ref> Jeremy Grayzel is CEO of CDM Publishing and Smart + Strong. He was president of VNU eMedia (now known as Nielsen Business Media). Ian Anderson is president of Smart + Strong. He was director of product development at VNU eMedia. Diane Anderson is vice president of integrated sales. She joined ''POZ'' in 2018.\n\nIn 2006, Regan Hofmann <ref>Miller, Lia; \n[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/13/business/media/13poz.html?_r=1&scp=4&sq=poz&st=cse&oref=slogin \u201cA Poz Columnist is Named Its Editor\u201d]; The New York Times; March 13, 2006</ref> became editor-in-chief of ''POZ''. She was the writer of the magazine's \u201cAnonymous\u201d column. Previously, Hofmann was editor-in-chief of ''New Jersey Life'' and founded ''Poets, Artists & Madmen''. She is now a consultant focused on strategy, communications and change in the field of global health.<ref>Regan Hofmann's Site, [http://www.reganhofmann.com/about \"About Regan\"]</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Oriol R. Gutierrez Jr.<ref>POZ.com, [http://www.poz.com/articles/oriol_gutierrez_poz_457_22836.shtml \"Oriol Gutierrez Named Editor-in-Chief of POZ\"]</ref> became editor-in-chief of ''POZ''. He was deputy editor since 2008. Previously, Gutierrez was managing editor of ''DiversityInc'', as well as cofounder, publisher and editor-in-chief of ''LGNY Latino''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.poz.com POZ.com]\n* [http://www.aidsmeds.com AIDSmeds.com]\n* [http://www.realhealthmag.com RealHealthMag.com]\n* [http://www.tusaludmag.com TuSaludMag.com]\n* [http://www.sanemag.com SaneMag.com]\n* [http://www.hepmag.com HepMag.com]\n* [http://www.cancerhealth.com CancerHealth.com]\n* [http://www.smartandstrong.com SmartAndStrong.com]\n\n[[Category:American news magazines]]\n[[Category:American eight times annually magazines]]\n[[Category:Health magazines]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in the United States]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Media portrayal of HIV/AIDS]]\n[[Category:American lifestyle magazines]]\n\n\n{{health-mag-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Senator2029", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:official website template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/POZ_(magazine)"}
