r|1978}}) <br> Assistant special teams coach & defensive assistant\n* [[New York Giants]] ({{NFL Year|1979}}) <br> Special teams coach & defensive assistant\n* New York Giants ({{NFL Year|1980}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1984}}) <br> Linebackers coach & special teams coach\n* New York Giants ({{NFL Year|1985}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1990}}) <br> Defensive coordinator\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ({{NFL Year|1991}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1995}}) <br> Head coach\n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|1996}}) <br> Assistant head coach & defensive backs coach\n* [[New York Jets]] ({{NFL Year|1997}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1999}}) <br> Assistant head coach & defensive coordinator\n* New England Patriots ({{NFL Year|2000}}\u2013present) <br> Head coach\n| highlights =\n'''As head coach:'''\n* 6\u00d7 [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XXXVI|XXXVI]], [[Super Bowl XXXVIII|XXXVIII]], [[Super Bowl XXXIX|XXXIX]], [[Super Bowl XLIX|XLIX]], [[Super Bowl LI|LI]], [[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]])\n* 3\u00d7 [[Associated Press NFL Coach of the Year Award|AP NFL Coach of the Year]] (2003, 2007, 2010)\n* First-team [[National Football League 2000s All-Decade Team|NFL 2000s All-Decade Team]]\n* [[National Football League 2010s All-Decade Team|NFL 2010s All-Decade Team]]\n* [[NFL 100th Anniversary All-Time Team]]\n;NFL coaching records\n* Most Super Bowl wins: 6\n* Most Super Bowl appearances: 9\n* Most NFL championships: 6 (tied)\n* Most playoff wins: 31\n\n'''As defensive coordinator:'''\n* 2\u00d7 [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XXI|XXI]], [[Super Bowl XXV|XXV]])\n| regular_record = {{Winning percentage|273|126|record=y}}\n| playoff_record = {{Winning percentage|31|12|record=y}}\n| overall_record = {{Winning percentage|304|137|record=y}}\n| pfrcoach = BeliBi0\n}}\n\n'''William Stephen Belichick''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u025b|l|\u1d7b|t\u0283|\u026a|k}} or {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u025b|l|\u1d7b|t\u0283|\u025b|k}}; born April 16, 1952) is an American professional [[American football|football]] coach who serves as the [[head coach#National Football League|head coach]] of the [[New England Patriots]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He exercises extensive authority over the Patriots' football operations, effectively making him the team's [[General manager (American football)|general manager]] as well.<ref name=patriotbio>{{cite web | title=New England Patriots' Biography of Bill Belichick | url=http://www.patriots.com/team/coaches/roster/bill-belichick | accessdate=July 5, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118105210/http://www.patriots.com/team/coaches/roster/bill-belichick | archive-date=January 18, 2017 | url-status=dead}}</ref> He holds numerous coaching records, including winning a record six [[Super Bowl]]s as the head coach of the Patriots, and two more as [[defensive coordinator]] for the [[New York Giants]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/02/04/belichick-brady-led-patriots-have-case-be-considered-sports-worlds-top-dynasty | title=The Belichick- and Brady-led Patriots have a case to be considered sports world\u2019s top dynasty | first=Neil | last=Greenberg | date=February 4, 2019 | work=The Washington Post | access-date=February 6, 2019}}</ref> He is widely considered to be one of the greatest coaches in NFL history by current and former players, his peers, and the press.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/page/greatestcoach7/greatest-coaches-nfl-history-bill-belichick | title=Greatest Coaches in NFL History \u2013 7. Bill Belichick: Attention to detail | date=June 5, 2013 | first=Kevin | last=Stone | website=ESPN.com | access-date=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBelichick began his coaching career in 1975 and became the [[defensive coordinator]] for [[New York Giants]] head coach [[Bill Parcells]] by 1985. Parcells and Belichick won two [[Super Bowl]]s together before Belichick left to become the head coach of the [[Cleveland Browns]] in 1991. He remained in Cleveland for five seasons but was fired following the team's [[1995 Cleveland Browns season|1995 season]]. He then rejoined Parcells, first in New England, where the team lost [[Super Bowl XXXI]], and later with the [[New York Jets]].\n\nAfter being named head coach of the Jets, Belichick resigned after only one day on the job to accept the head coaching job for the New England Patriots on January 27, 2000. Since then, he has led the Patriots to 17 [[AFC East]] division titles, 13 appearances in the [[AFC Championship Game]], and nine Super Bowl appearances, with a record six wins.  In total Belichick has won eight Super Bowl titles and finished as runner-up four times from his combined time as an assistant and head coach.\n\nBelichick is the NFL's longest-tenured active head coach, as well as the first all-time in [[List of National Football League head coaches by playoff record|playoff coaching wins]] with 31 and third in [[List of National Football League head coaches with 50 wins|regular season coaching wins in the NFL]] with 261.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2017/11/19/patriots-bill-belichick-tom-landry-nfl-all-time-wins-list/ | title=Bill Belichick Passes Tom Landry On NFL's All-Time Wins List | date=November 19, 2017 | publisher=CBS Boston | access-date=November 22, 2017}}</ref> He is one of only three head coaches who have won six NFL titles.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/25923676 | title=Bill Belichick joins George Halas, Curly Lambeau with six NFL titles | first=Mike | last=Reiss | date=February 4, 2019 | publisher=ESPN | access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref> He was named the [[Associated Press|AP]] [[National Football League Coach of the Year Award|NFL Coach of the Year]] for the [[2003 NFL season|2003]], [[2007 NFL season|2007]], and [[2010 NFL season|2010 seasons]]. Belichick is the only active head coach named to the [[National Football League 100th Anniversary All-Time Team]].\n\n{{TOClimit|3}}\n\n==Early life==\nBelichick was born on April 16, 1952, in [[Nashville, Tennessee]],<ref>BBC Sport. February 1, 2015 [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/american-football/31056519 Super Bowl: Bill Belichick and Tom Brady head for fourth win]</ref> the son of Jeannette (Munn) and [[Steve Belichick]] (born Stephen Bili\u010di\u0107).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2005/11/24/given_proper_naval_sendoff/?page=full |title=Given proper naval sendoff |work=boston.com | first=Dan|last=Shaughnessy|date=November 24, 2005}}</ref> Bill was named after [[College Football Hall of Fame]] coach [[Bill Edwards (American football coach)|Bill Edwards]], who was his [[Godparent|godfather]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=NFL Head Coaches: A Biographical Dictionary, 1920\u20132011|last=Maxymuk|first=John|year=2012|page=77}}</ref> Belichick is of [[Croats|Croatian]] ancestry,<ref name=BG051121>{{cite news | url = https://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2005/11/21/belichick_learned_well_from_dad/?page=full | title = Belichick learned well from dad | first = Bob | last = Ryan | work = Boston Globe | date = November 21, 2005 }}</ref> and his paternal grandparents, Ivan Bili\u010di\u0107 and Marija (Mary) Barkovi\u0107, emigrated from the Croatian village of [[Dragani\u0107, Karlovac County|Dragani\u0107]], [[Karlovac]], in 1897, settling in [[Monessen, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"granddad\">{{in lang|hr}} [http://www.jutarnji.hr/clanak/art-2007,2,22,belichick_patriots,63704.jl Bill Belichick Djed iz Dragani\u0107a uvijek mi je pri\u010dao o Hrvatskoj], [[Jutarnji list]], February 2, 2007</ref>\n\nHe was raised in [[Annapolis, Maryland]],<ref>[http://www.patriots.com/team/coaches/bill-belichick/5c49726a-15ad-4e5a-9246-a30417694eb0 New England Patriots: Bill Belichick<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925061717/http://www.patriots.com/team/coaches/bill-belichick/5c49726a-15ad-4e5a-9246-a30417694eb0 |date=September 25, 2011 }}</ref> where his father was an assistant football coach at the [[United States Naval Academy]]. Belichick has cited his father as one of his most important football mentors, and Belichick often studied football with him.<ref name=greatdefender>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Chris B.|title=The Great Defender|url=http://grantland.com/features/new-england-patriots-bill-belichick-coaching-legacy-super-bowl-seattle-seahawks/|accessdate=February 3, 2015|publisher=Grantland|date=January 30, 2015}}</ref> Bill reportedly learned to break down game films at a young age by watching his father and the Navy staff do their jobs.<ref>[[David Halberstam|Halberstam, David]]. ''The Education of a Coach.'' Hyperion, 2005. ({{ISBN|1-4013-0879-1}})</ref> He graduated from [[Annapolis High School (Maryland)|Annapolis High School]] in 1970 with classmate [[Sally Brice-O'Hara]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-coast-guard-admiral-20120428-story.html|title=The Interview: Sally Brice-O'Hara|last=Sun|first=Candus Thomson, The Baltimore|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=December 24, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> While there, he played [[American football|football]] and [[lacrosse]], with the latter being his favorite sport.<ref>[http://www.hometownannapolis.com/news/spo/2008/02/03-33/Annapolis-XOXO-Bill-Belichick.html?ne=1 Hulette, Elisabeth. \"Annapolis XOXO Bill Belichick,\" ''The Capital'' (Annapolis, MD), Sunday, February 3, 2008.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324190324/http://www.hometownannapolis.com/news/spo/2008/02/03-33/Annapolis-XOXO-Bill-Belichick.html?ne=1 |date=March 24, 2012 }}</ref> He enrolled at [[Phillips Academy]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts]], for a postgraduate year, with the intention of improving his grades and test scores to be admitted into a quality college.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/eticket/story?page=adams |last=Thompson|first=Wright|title= Who Is This Guy?|publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=September 25, 2004 |accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref> The school honored him 40 years later by inducting him into its Athletics Hall of Honor in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andover.edu/Alumni/HallofHonor/Pages/PastRecipients.aspx |title=Athletics Hall of Honor Inductees \u2013 Phillips Academy |publisher=Andover.edu |date= |accessdate=May 27, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323203559/http://www.andover.edu/Alumni/HallofHonor/Pages/PastRecipients.aspx |archivedate=March 23, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nBelichick subsequently attended [[Wesleyan University]] in Middletown, Connecticut, where he played center and tight end. In addition to being a member of the football team, he played [[lacrosse]] and [[squash (sport)|squash]], serving as the captain of the lacrosse team during his senior season. A member of [[Chi Psi]] fraternity,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wesleyanargus.com/2009/10/13/the-lost-brotherhood-the-tragic-history-of-chi-psi-at-wesleyan/ |last=Pottle|first=Justin|title=The Lost Brotherhood: the Tragic History of Chi Psi at Wesleyan|work=The Wesleyan Argus |date=October 13, 2009 |accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref> he earned a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[economics]] in 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patriots.com/team/index.cfm?ac=coachbio&bio=506 |title=Bill Belichick, Head Coach (Official Biography) \u2013 New England Patriots |publisher=Patriots.com |date= |accessdate=May 27, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070602084910/http://www.patriots.com/team/index.cfm?ac=coachbio&bio=506 |archivedate=June 2, 2007 |df= }}</ref> He would eventually be part of the inaugural induction class into the university's Athletics Hall of Fame in spring 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wesleyan.edu/athletics/halloffame/inductee-information.html |title=Athletics Hall of Fame, Inductee Information \u2013 Wesleyan University |publisher=Wesleyan.edu |date= |accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\n\n===Early coaching positions===\nAfter graduating, Belichick took a $25-per-week job as an assistant to [[Baltimore Colts]] head coach [[Ted Marchibroda]] in [[1975 NFL season|1975]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=1688687 | title=Preparation leads Belichick to top | publisher=ESPN.com | author=Jeff Reynolds | date=December 20, 2003}}</ref> In [[1976 NFL season|1976]], he joined the [[Detroit Lions]] as their assistant special teams coach before adding [[tight end]]s and [[wide receiver]]s to his coaching duties in [[1977 NFL season|1977]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2014/11/23/patriots-coach-belichick-fond-lions-memories/19436945/ |title=Patriots coach Belichick is fond of his Lions memories |last=Katzenstein |first=Josh |work=Detroit News |access-date=December 28, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> He spent the [[1978 NFL season|1978 season]] with the [[Denver Broncos]] as their assistant special teams coach and defensive assistant.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.denverbroncos.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Patriots-head-coach-Bill-Belichick-on-year-coaching-in-Denver/bd8f14b7-3f65-4119-8473-1bc7fa7a0d2d |title=Patriots head coach Bill Belichick on year coaching in Denver |last=DiLalla |first=Eric |work=Denver Broncos |access-date=December 28, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228115214/http://www.denverbroncos.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Patriots-head-coach-Bill-Belichick-on-year-coaching-in-Denver/bd8f14b7-3f65-4119-8473-1bc7fa7a0d2d |archive-date=December 28, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===New York Giants (1979\u20131990)===\nIn [[1979 NFL season|1979]], Belichick began a 12-year stint with the [[New York Giants]] alongside head coach [[Ray Perkins (wide receiver)|Ray Perkins]] as a defensive assistant and special teams coach.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2017/11/02/bill-belichick-press-conferences-special-teams-quotes |title=Bill Belichick and special teams: a love story |last=Jones |first=Jonathan |work=Sports Illustrated |access-date=December 28, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> He added [[linebacker]]s coaching to his duties in [[1980 NFL season|1980]] and was named defensive coordinator in [[1985 NFL season|1985]] under head coach [[Bill Parcells]], who had replaced Perkins in 1983. The Giants won [[Super Bowl XXI]] and [[Super Bowl XXV]] following the 1986 and 1990 seasons.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/198701250den.htm |title=Super Bowl XXI \u2013 New York Giants vs. Denver Broncos \u2013 January 25th, 1987 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/heres-why-bill-belichick-was-wearing-10-huge-rings-at-the-patriots-ring-party/ |title=Here's why Bill Belichick was wearing 10 huge rings at the Patriots' ring party |last=Breech |first=John |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=December 28, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> His defensive game plan from the [[New York Giants]]' 20\u201319 upset of the [[Buffalo Bills]] in Super Bowl XXV has been placed in the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vrentas|first1=Jenny|title=Bill Belichick's Super Bowl XXV Game Plan|url=http://mmqb.si.com/2014/05/14/nfl-history-in-95-objects-bill-belichick-super-xxv-game-plan/|publisher=The MMQB|accessdate=January 27, 2015|date=May 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Browns (1991\u20131995)===\nFrom 1991 until 1995, Belichick was the head coach of the [[Cleveland Browns]]. During his tenure in Cleveland, he compiled a 36\u201344 record, leading the team to the playoffs in 1994, his only winning year with the team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/ |title=Cleveland Browns Team Encyclopedia |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> Coincidentally, his one playoff victory during his Browns tenure was achieved against the [[1994 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] in the [[1994\u201395 NFL playoffs#AFC: Cleveland Browns 20, New England Patriots 13|Wild Card Round]] during that postseason.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/199501010cle.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 New England Patriots at Cleveland Browns \u2013 January 1st, 1995 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> In Belichick's last season in Cleveland, the Browns finished 5\u201311, despite starting 3\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1995.htm |title=1995 Cleveland Browns Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> One of his most controversial moves was cutting quarterback [[Bernie Kosar]] midway through the 1993 season. Kosar was signed by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] two days later and won a Super Bowl with the Cowboys in [[Super Bowl XXVIII]]. In November 1995, in the middle of the ongoing football season, Browns owner [[Art Modell]] had announced he would move his franchise to [[Baltimore]] after the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/art-modell-announces-browns-are-moving-to-baltimore |title=Art Modell announces Browns are moving to Baltimore |website=HISTORY |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102050655/https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/art-modell-announces-browns-are-moving-to-baltimore |archive-date=January 2, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After first being given assurances that he would coach the new team that would later become the [[Baltimore Ravens]], Belichick was instead fired on February 14, 1996, one week after the shift was officially announced.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2202&dat=19960215&id=2xEmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yf0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6697,1482003|title=Modell fires Bill Belichick|newspaper=Gettysburg Times|date=February 15, 1996|page=B2}}</ref>\n\n===New England Patriots (1996)===\nAfter his dismissal by the Cleveland Browns, Belichick served under Parcells again as assistant head coach and defensive backs coach with the Patriots for the 1996 season. The Patriots finished with an 11\u20135 record and won the [[1996\u201397 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship: New England Patriots 20, Jacksonville Jaguars 6|AFC Championship]] over the [[1996 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], but they lost to the [[1996 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]] in [[Super Bowl XXXI]] amid rumors of Parcells's impending defection.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/1996.htm |title=1996 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/199701260gnb.htm |title=Super Bowl XXXI \u2013 New England Patriots vs. Green Bay Packers \u2013 January 26th, 1997 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New York Jets (1997\u20131999)===\nBelichick had two stints as the head coach of the New York Jets without ever coaching a game.\n\nIn February 1997, Belichick, who had been an assistant coach under Bill Parcells with the New York Giants and New England Patriots, was named the Jets interim head coach while the Jets and Patriots continued to negotiate compensation to release Parcells from his contract with the Patriots and allow Parcells to coach the Jets.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1997-02-05/sports/1997036128_1_bill-parcells-new-york-jets-patriots |title=End around: Parcells gets consultant job Jets hire Belichick until ex-Patriots coach is free to take over |work=[[Baltimore Sun]] |author=Vito Stellino |date=February 5, 1997 |accessdate=November 16, 2014}}</ref> Six days later, the Patriots and Jets reached an agreement that allowed Parcells to coach the Jets, and Belichick became the team's assistant head coach and defensive coordinator.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1997-02-11/sports/sp-27483_1_bill-parcells |title=Parcells to coach Jets in 1997 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |author=Jim Hodges |date=February 11, 1997 |accessdate=November 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhen Parcells stepped down as head coach after the 1999 season, he had already arranged with team management to have Belichick succeed him. However, Belichick would be the New York Jets' head coach for only one day. On January 4, 2000, when Belichick was introduced as head coach to the media\u2014the day after his hiring was publicized\u2014he turned it into a surprise resignation announcement. Before taking the podium, he scrawled a resignation note on a napkin that read, in its entirety, ''\"I resign as HC of the NYJ.\"'' He then delivered a half-hour speech explaining his resignation to the assembled press corps.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/writers/pete_mcentegart/07/28/ten.spot/index.html | title=The 10 spot | publisher=SI.com | author=Pete McEntegart | date=July 28, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026030024/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/writers/pete_mcentegart/07/28/ten.spot/index.html|archivedate=October 26, 2012|accessdate=May 10, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSoon after this bizarre turn of events, he was introduced as the Patriots' 12th full-time head coach, succeeding the recently fired [[Pete Carroll]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nep.247sports.com/Bolt/TBT-Bill-Belichick-introduced-as-Patriots-head-coach-in-2000-49987623 |title=TBT: Bill Belichick introduced as Patriots head coach in 2000 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> The Patriots had tried to hire him away from Parcells/the Jets in the past.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} Parcells and the Jets claimed that Belichick was still under contract to the Jets, and demanded compensation from the Patriots. NFL Commissioner [[Paul Tagliabue]] agreed, and the Patriots gave the Jets a first-round draft pick in [[2000 NFL Draft|2000]] in exchange for the right to hire Belichick.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.patsfans.com/stories/display_story.php?story_id=2920 | title=How exactly will history judge Parcells? (Pt 3) | publisher=BosSports.net | author=Bob George | date=January 13, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060908123347/http://www.patsfans.com/stories/display_story.php?story_id=2920|archivedate=September 8, 2006|accessdate=May 10, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===New England Patriots (2000\u2013present)===\nSoon after hiring Belichick, owner [[Robert Kraft]] gave him near-complete control over the team's football operations, effectively making him the team's general manager as well. Until 2009, Belichick split many of the duties normally held by a general manager on other clubs with player personnel director [[Scott Pioli]], though Belichick had the final say on football matters.<ref>Bell, Jarrett. [https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/2005draft/2005-04-21-patriots-draft_x.htm Piecing the Patriots together]. [[USA Today]], April 21, 2005.</ref> Pioli left for the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] after the 2008 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/14/sports/football/14chiefs.html |title=Scott Pioli Leaves Patriots to Be Chiefs\u2019 General Manager |last=Battista |first=Judy |date=January 13, 2009 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Patriots went 5\u201311 in the [[2000 New England Patriots season|2000]] regular season and missed the [[2000\u201301 NFL playoffs|playoffs]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2000.htm |title=2000 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> To date, this is Belichick's only losing season with the Patriots.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/BeliBi0.htm |title=Bill Belichick Record, Statistics, and Category Ranks |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== 2001\u20132004 ====\nIn 2001, the Patriots went 11\u20135 in the regular season, and defeated the [[2001 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]] (in the \"[[Tuck Rule Game]]\") and [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] on the way to the Super Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200201190nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Oakland Raiders at New England Patriots \u2013 January 19th, 2002 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200201270pit.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 New England Patriots at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 January 27th, 2002 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> In [[Super Bowl XXXVI]], Belichick's defense held the [[2001 St. Louis Rams season|St. Louis Rams]]' offense, which had averaged 31 points during the season, to 17 points, and the Patriots won on a last second field goal by [[Adam Vinatieri]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200202030nwe.htm |title=Super Bowl XXXVI \u2013 St. Louis Rams vs. New England Patriots \u2013 February 3rd, 2002 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> The win was the first [[Super Bowl]] championship in Patriots history.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2002/02/04/patriots-shock-nfl-defeat-rams-win-super-bowl/7mbT3QFE048ZtrA5s2XP1H/story.html |title=Patriots shock NFL, defeat Rams to win Super Bowl \u2013 The Boston Globe |last=Cafardo |first=Nick|authorlink=Nick Cafardo |work=Boston Globe |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following season (2002)\u2014the first in [[Gillette Stadium]]\u2014the Patriots went 9\u20137 and missed the [[2002\u201303 NFL playoffs|playoffs]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2002.htm |title=2002 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> New England finished with the same record as the [[2002 New York Jets season|New York Jets]] and the [[2002 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], but the Jets won the AFC East title as a result of the third tiebreaker (record among common opponents).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2002/ |title=2002 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bob Kraft-George Bush-Bill Belichick.jpg|thumbnail|Belichick (right) at the Patriots visit to the White House in 2004|left]]\nThe Patriots' 2003 season started with a 31\u20130 loss to the [[2003 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] in Week 1, a few days after they released team defensive captain [[Lawyer Milloy]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/510051541/Patriots-cut-captain-Lawyer-Milloy.html |title=Patriots cut captain Lawyer Milloy |date=September 3, 2003 |work=DeseretNews.com |access-date=December 28, 2017 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200309070buf.htm |title=New England Patriots at Buffalo Bills \u2013 September 7th, 2003 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> However, they dominated through the remainder of the season to finish 14\u20132, setting a new franchise record for wins in a season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/index.htm |title=Boston/New England Patriots Team Encyclopedia |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> In the final week of the regular season, the Patriots avenged their loss to the Bills by the same 31\u20130 score.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200312270nwe.htm |title=Buffalo Bills at New England Patriots \u2013 December 27th, 2003 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> They defeated the [[2003 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]] in the [[2003\u201304 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 17, Tennessee Titans 14|Divisional Round]]. Playing against the [[2003 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] and Co-[[NFL MVP|MVP]] [[Peyton Manning]] in the [[2003\u201304 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship: New England Patriots 24, Indianapolis Colts 14|AFC Championship]] ([[Steve McNair]] of the Titans was also Co-MVP), the Patriots recorded four interceptions, and advanced to [[Super Bowl XXXVIII]], where they defeated the [[2003 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] 32\u201329 on a late [[Adam Vinatieri]] field goal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200402010car.htm |title=Super Bowl XXXVIII \u2013 New England Patriots vs. Carolina Panthers \u2013 February 1st, 2004 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.si.com/vault/2004/02/09/361576/fight-to-the-finish-new-england-and-carolina-went-toe-to-toe-but-tom-brady-kept-his-cool-and-led-the-patriots-to-their-second-nfl-title-in-three-years | title=Fight to the Finish | last=Silver | first=Michael | work=Sports Illustrated | date=February 9, 2004 | access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> Belichick also was awarded with the [[NFL Coach of the Year Award]].\n\nIn 2004, the Patriots once again finished with a 14\u20132 record, and they defeated the [[2004 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] in the [[2004\u201305 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 20, Indianapolis Colts 3|Divisional Round]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2004.htm |title=2004 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200501160nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Indianapolis Colts at New England Patriots \u2013 January 16th, 2005 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> They opened the season at 6\u20130, which combined with the 15 straight wins to end the previous season, gave New England 21 consecutive victories to break the record for most wins in a row formerly held by the Miami Dolphins with 18 straight victories in the 1972 and 1973 seasons. They defeated the [[2004 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] in the [[2004\u201305 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship: New England Patriots 41, Pittsburgh Steelers 27|AFC Championship]]. In [[Super Bowl XXXIX]], the Patriots beat the [[2004 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] and became only the second team to win three Super Bowls in four years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200502060nwe.htm |title=Super Bowl XXXIX \u2013 Philadelphia Eagles vs. New England Patriots \u2013 February 6th, 2005 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/patriots/2016/01/super_bowl_xxxix_patriots_edge_eagles_for_3rd_super_bowl_title |title=Super Bowl XXXIX: Patriots edge Eagles for 3rd Super Bowl title |work=Boston Herald |access-date=December 28, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228171610/http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/patriots/2016/01/super_bowl_xxxix_patriots_edge_eagles_for_3rd_super_bowl_title |archive-date=December 28, 2017 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Belichick is the only coach to accomplish the feat as the Dallas Cowboys had two head coaches in the stretch they won three of four from 1992\u20131995.\n\n==== 2005\u20132009 ====\nWith a new defensive coordinator in [[Eric Mangini]] and no named offensive coordinator, the Patriots went 10\u20136 in the 2005 season and defeated the [[2005 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]] in the [[2005\u201306 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 28, Jacksonville Jaguars 3|Wild Card Round]] before losing to the [[2005 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] in the [[2005\u201306 NFL playoffs#AFC: Denver Broncos 27, New England Patriots 13|Divisional Round]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2005.htm |title=2005 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200601070nwe.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Jacksonville Jaguars at New England Patriots \u2013 January 7th, 2006 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200601140den.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 New England Patriots at Denver Broncos \u2013 January 14th, 2006 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> Earlier, with a season-opening win over the [[2005 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], Belichick notched his 54th win with the Patriots, passing [[Mike Holovak]] as the winningest coach in Patriots history.\n\nThe Patriots finished with a 12\u20134 record in the 2006 season and defeated the [[2006 New York Jets season|New York Jets]] by a score of 37\u201316 in the [[2006\u201307 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 37, New York Jets 16|Wild Card Round]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2006.htm |title=2006 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200701070nwe.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 New York Jets at New England Patriots \u2013 January 7th, 2007 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> They then beat the [[2006 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]] the next week in the [[2006\u201307 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 24, San Diego Chargers 21|Divisional Round]], before losing to the eventual [[Super Bowl XLI]] winner [[2006 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] in the [[2006\u201307 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship: Indianapolis Colts 38, New England Patriots 34|AFC Championship]] by a score of 38\u201334.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200701140sdg.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 New England Patriots at San Diego Chargers \u2013 January 14th, 2007 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200701210clt.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 New England Patriots at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 January 21st, 2007 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> The Patriots led 21\u20133 mid-way during the second quarter, but the Colts mounted one of the great comebacks in playoff history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greatest Comebacks in NFL History|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/football-history/greatest-comebacks-in-nfl-history/#postseason|website=profootballhof.com|publisher=Pro Football Hall of Fame|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bill Belichick 8-28-09 Patriots-vs-Redskins.jpg|thumb|Belichick during an August 28, 2009 preseason game against the [[Washington Redskins]]]]\n\nIn 2007, Belichick led the Patriots to the first [[2007 New England Patriots season|perfect regular season]] since the introduction of the 16-game regular season schedule in 1978, only the fourth team to do so in National Football League history after the 1934<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobears.com/tradition/history_30s.asp|title=Highlights from the 1930s \u2013 Chicago Bears|publisher=Chicagobears.com|accessdate=May 27, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712155734/http://www.chicagobears.com/tradition/history_30s.asp|archive-date=July 12, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and 1942 Chicago Bears<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobears.com/tradition/history_40s.asp|title=Highlights from the 1940s \u2013 Chicago Bears|publisher=Chicagobears.com|accessdate=May 27, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709135320/http://www.chicagobears.com/tradition/history_40s.asp|archive-date=July 9, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[1972 Miami Dolphins season|1972 Miami Dolphins]]. In the [[2007\u201308 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 31, Jacksonville Jaguars 20|Divisional Round]] of the playoffs, they defeated the [[2007 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]] by a score of 31\u201320. In the [[2007\u201308 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship: New England Patriots 21, San Diego Chargers 12|AFC Championship]], the Patriots defeated the [[2007 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]] by a score of 21\u201312. The Patriots were upset in [[Super Bowl XLII]] by the [[2007 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], his former team, due to the defense [[Helmet Catch|allowing a famous play to David Tyree]] near the end of regulation<ref>{{cite news|title=Sweet 16 and 0 for Patriots|work=Denver Post|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2007/12/29/its-sweet-16-0-for-patriots/|accessdate=December 29, 2007}}</ref> The Patriots' failure to attain a \"perfect season\" (undefeated and untied, including playoffs) preserved the [[Miami Dolphins]] as the sole team to do so, having finished their 1972 regular season at 14\u20130 and having won three games in the playoffs. Only two other teams in professional football have recorded a perfect season\u2014the [[1948 Cleveland Browns season|1948 Cleveland Browns]] (14\u20130) of the then [[All-America Football Conference]] and the [[1948 Calgary Stampeders season|1948 Calgary Stampeders]] (12\u20130) of the [[Canadian Football League]]. No team in the former American Football League had a perfect season.\n\nIn the Patriots' 2008 season-opener against the [[2008 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], quarterback [[Tom Brady]] suffered a season-ending injury in the first quarter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d80a95089/article/brady-to-have-seasonending-knee-surgery-will-be-placed-on-ir |title=Brady to have season-ending knee surgery, will be placed on IR |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> Backup quarterback [[Matt Cassel]] was named the starter for the remainder of the season. However, with a win in Week 2, the Patriots broke their own record for regular season wins in a row with 21 (2006\u201308). After losing over a dozen players to the injured reserve list, including [[Rodney Harrison]], [[Adalius Thomas]], and [[Laurence Maroney]], the Patriots still managed their league-leading eighth consecutive season with a winning record, going 11\u20135.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2008.htm |title=2008 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> Nevertheless, the Patriots, who finished second in the [[AFC East]], missed the [[2008\u201309 NFL playoffs|playoffs]] for the first time since 2002, losing on tiebreakers to the [[2008 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] (who won the division on the fourth tiebreaker, better conference record) and the [[2008 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] (who beat out the Patriots for the last playoff spot due to a better conference record).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2008/ |title=2008 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> The [[1985 Denver Broncos season|1985 Denver Broncos]] are the only other 11-win team to miss the playoffs in a 16-game season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://history.denverbroncos.com/season/1985/ |title=1985 \u2013 Denver Broncos History |website=Denver Broncos |language=en-US |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, with a fully healthy Tom Brady back as the starting quarterback, Belichick was able to guide the Patriots to yet another AFC East division title with a 10\u20136 record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2009.htm |title=2009 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> However, the Patriots lost to the [[2009 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] in the [[2009\u201310 NFL playoffs#AFC: Baltimore Ravens 33, New England Patriots 14|Wild Card Round]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201001100nwe.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots \u2013 January 10th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== 2010\u2013present ====\n\nIn the 2010 season, Belichick and the Patriots finished with a 14\u20132 record for the top seed in the AFC.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2010.htm |title=2010 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> However, their postseason ended quickly with a 28\u201321 loss to the [[2010 New York Jets season|New York Jets]] in the [[2010\u201311 NFL playoffs#AFC: New York Jets 28, New England Patriots 21|Divisional Round]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201101160nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 New York Jets at New England Patriots \u2013 January 16th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2011 season, the Patriots topped the AFC with a 13\u20133 record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2011.htm |title=2011 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> Following a victory over the [[2011 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] in the [[2011\u201312 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 45, Denver Broncos 10|Divisional Round]], the Patriots won the [[2011\u201312 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 23, Baltimore Ravens 20|AFC Championship]] game beating the [[2011 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] 23\u201320 when the Ravens failed to score a touchdown and Baltimore's kicker, [[Billy Cundiff]], missed a routine 32-yard field goal attempt to tie the game and send it into overtime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201140nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Denver Broncos at New England Patriots \u2013 January 14th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/football/10176603-419/billy-cundiff-ravens-miss-super-chance.html |title=Billy Cundiff, Ravens miss Super chance \u2013 Chicago Sun-Times |publisher=Suntimes.com |date=January 23, 2012 |accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref> This sent New England to their fifth Super Bowl under Belichick. In [[Super Bowl XLVI]], the Patriots lost in the Super Bowl XLII rematch to the [[2011 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] by a score of 21\u201317.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/Super-Bowl-XLVI-New-York-Giants-New-England-Patriots-postgame-020512 |title=New York Giants beat the New England Patriots to win Super Bowl XLVI \u2013 NFL News &#124; FOX Sports on MSN |publisher=Msn.foxsports.com |date=February 6, 2012 |accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bill Belichick 2012 Shankbone.JPG|thumb|right|Belichick at the [[Time 100|2012 Time 100 gala]]]]\n\nOn September 26, 2012, following a 31\u201330 loss to the [[2012 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Belichick was fined $50,000 for grabbing a replacement official's arm while asking for more specific clarity on a ruling after Baltimore had narrowly converted a last-second field goal attempt to secure the win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/belichick-fined-50k-shanahan-25k-174534755--nfl.html |title=Belichick fined 50K, Kyle Shanahan 25K by NFL \u2013 Yahoo! Sports |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=September 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929012115/http://sports.yahoo.com/news/belichick-fined-50k-shanahan-25k-174534755--nfl.html |archivedate=September 29, 2012 |df= }}</ref> The Patriots finished the 2012 regular season with a 12\u20134 record. In the [[2012\u201313 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 41, Houston Texans 28|Divisional Round]], they defeated the [[2012 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] by a score of 41\u201328 and made it to the [[2012\u201313 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: Baltimore Ravens 28, New England Patriots 13|AFC Championship]], where they lost to the [[2012 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] by a score of 28\u201313, ending their season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2012.htm |title=2012 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201301200nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots \u2013 January 20th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBelichick's Patriots began the 2013 season with much upheaval on the offensive side of the ball with the injury of Rob Gronkowski, the arrest and subsequent release of [[Aaron Hernandez]], the departures of Wes Welker to the Denver Broncos and Danny Woodhead to the San Diego Chargers in free agency, and the release of Brandon Lloyd. To replace them, the Patriots signed [[Danny Amendola]] in free agency, drafted rookies [[Aaron Dobson]] and [[Josh Boyce]], and signed undrafted rookie free agent [[Kenbrell Thompkins]]. The team ended the season with a 12\u20134 record, winning the AFC East and securing a playoff berth and a first-round bye, seeding second in the AFC standings.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2013.htm |title=2013 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> In the [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 43, Indianapolis Colts 22|Divisional Round]], they defeated the [[2013 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] by a score of 43\u201322.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201401110nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Indianapolis Colts at New England Patriots \u2013 January 11th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> They lost to the [[2013 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] in the [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: Denver Broncos 26, New England Patriots 16|AFC Championship]] by a score of 26\u201316.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201401190den.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 New England Patriots at Denver Broncos \u2013 January 19th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2014 season, Belichick's Patriots started 2\u20132.  Following a loss to the Kansas City Chiefs, Belichick famously uttered \"We're on to Cincinnati!\" in response to criticisms of his team, Brady in particular.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2217320-bill-belichick-answers-were-on-to-cincinnati-to-5-questions-in-presser|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|author=Kyle Newport |date=October 1, 2014}}</ref> Ultimately, they recorded a 12\u20134 record for the third straight season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2014.htm |title=2014 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> In the [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 35, Baltimore Ravens 31|Divisional Round]], they defeated the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] by a score of 35\u201331.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501100nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots \u2013 January 10th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> In the [[Deflategate|AFC Championship]], they defeated the Indianapolis Colts by a score of 45\u20137.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501180nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Indianapolis Colts at New England Patriots \u2013 January 18th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> They reached [[Super Bowl XLIX]], where they defeated the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] by a score of 28\u201324.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201502010sea.htm |title=Super Bowl XLIX \u2013 Seattle Seahawks vs. New England Patriots \u2013 February 1st, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> With his fourth championship as head coach, Belichick tied [[Chuck Noll]] for most wins by a head coach in a Super Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2015/02/02/what-made-bill-belichick-crack-with-emotion-after-fourth-title/ |title=What made Bill Belichick crack with emotion after fourth title |last=Serby |first=Steve |date=February 2, 2015 |website=New York Post |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>  \n\n[[File:P042315PS-0604 (20282065394).jpg|thumb|left|Belichick with President [[Barack Obama]] and [[Robert Kraft]]\n]]\n\nIn the 2015 season, Belichick's Patriots recorded a 12\u20134 record for the fourth straight season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2015.htm |title=2014 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> They defeated the [[2015 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] in the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 27, Kansas City Chiefs 20|Divisional Round]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601160nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Kansas City Chiefs at New England Patriots \u2013 January 16th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#AFC: Denver Broncos 20, New England Patriots 18|AFC Championship]], they lost to the eventual [[Super Bowl 50]] champion [[2015 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] by a score of 20\u201318.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601240den.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 New England Patriots at Denver Broncos \u2013 January 24th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2016 season, Belichick's Patriots recorded a 14\u20132 record, which earned them the #1 seed for the AFC playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2016.htm |title=2016 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> In the [[2016\u201317 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 34, Houston Texans 16|Divisional Round]], they defeated the [[2016 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201701140nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Houston Texans at New England Patriots \u2013 January 14th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2016\u201317 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 36, Pittsburgh Steelers 17|AFC Championship]], they defeated the [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201701220nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Pittsburgh Steelers at New England Patriots \u2013 January 22nd, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> They reached [[Super Bowl LI]], where they defeated the [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] in a comeback victory by a score of 34\u201328 in overtime.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Wesseling | first1=Chris | title=Patriots erase deficit, defeat Falcons in Super Bowl LI | date=February 5, 2017 | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000783692/article/patriots-erase-deficit-defeat-falcons-in-super-bowl-li | publisher=NFL | accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> The Patriots were down 28\u20133 at one point in the third quarter.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201702050atl.htm | title=Super Bowl LI \u2013 New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons \u2013 February 5th, 2017 | accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> With the victory, Belichick won his record fifth Super Bowl title as a head coach.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/05/sports/new-england-patriots-beat-atlanta-falcons-super-bowl.html |title=Patriots Mount a Comeback for the Ages to Win a Fifth Super Bowl |last=Shpigel |first=Ben |date=February 5, 2017 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2017 season, Belichick's Patriots went 13\u20133, setting an NFL record eighth consecutive 12-or-more-win seasons, capturing their ninth consecutive AFC East title and their 15th of the last 17 seasons. They defeated the [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]] in the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 35, Tennessee Titans 14|Divisional Round]] by a score of 35\u201314, and the [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]] in the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 24, Jacksonville Jaguars 20|AFC Championship]] by a score of 24\u201320, claiming their second AFC title in two years, while also extending their record of consecutive AFC Championship appearances with seven.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801130nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots \u2013 January 13th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801210nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Jacksonville Jaguars at New England Patriots \u2013 January 21st, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> [[Super Bowl LII]] was Belichick's eighth title game as head coach and his eleventh overall in any capacity, which was also the Patriot's tenth appearance, all extending NFL records. ''The Ringer'' wrote that Belichick's \"team is different from many of New England's famous teams from the previous decade: The first iteration of the Patriots dynasty relied on defense. This year, they are 29th in yards allowed (though fifth in points allowed) and instead have perfected the art of situational football\". The latter Patriots teams have been noted for mounting [[Clutch (sports)|late comebacks]] in playoff games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theringer.com/nfl-playoffs/2018/1/22/16920298/super-bowl-new-england-patriots-tom-brady-bill-belichick-hate|title=Why the NFL Needs the New England Patriots|first=Kevin|last=Clark|date=January 22, 2018|website=The Ringer}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/how-tom-brady-became-the-king-of-comebacks/|title=How Tom Brady Became The King Of Comebacks|first=Michael|last=Salfino|date=January 25, 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the Patriots fell to the [[2017 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] in [[Super Bowl LII]], 41\u201333, as [[Nick Foles]] repeated his dominant [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#NFC Championship Game: Philadelphia Eagles 38, Minnesota Vikings 7|NFC Championship game]] performance and led Philadelphia to victory in a high-scoring game. The Patriots were down early, as they have been in most of their Super Bowl wins. However, they could not make a comeback this time, although they came very close. The Eagles defense strip-sacked Tom Brady to get the ball back with about 2 minutes to go in the 4th quarter. The Patriots did get the ball again before the end of the game, but they ran out of time to score.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201802040nwe.htm |title=Super Bowl LII \u2013 Philadelphia Eagles vs. New England Patriots \u2013 February 4th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 season, Belichick's Patriots went 11\u20135 failing to win more than 12 games for the first time since 2009. The Patriots still captured their 10th consecutive AFC East Title and their 16th of the last 18 years. They defeated the [[2018 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]] in the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 41, Los Angeles Chargers 28|Divisional Round]] by a score of 41\u201328 and the [[2018 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] in the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 37, Kansas City Chiefs 31 (OT)|AFC Championship]] 37\u201331 in a tough overtime game in Kansas City to advance to their third straight Super Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201901130nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Los Angeles Chargers at New England Patriots \u2013 January 13th, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201901200kan.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 New England Patriots at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 January 20th, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> In [[Super Bowl LIII]], the Patriots defeated the [[2018 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]] 13\u20133 to give Belichick his 6th Super Bowl championship as a head coach and his eighth overall to have the most Super Bowl rings in NFL History. His six championships matched both [[George Halas]] and [[Curly Lambeau]] for most championships as a coach. The Patriots defense held the Rams offense to 260 total yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201902030ram.htm |title=Super Bowl LIII \u2013 Los Angeles Rams vs. New England Patriots \u2013 February 3rd, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/e42e7e69d5ec47f587972480cb69c59a |title=Pats' Belichick joins Halas, Lambeau with 6 championships |last=Odum |first=Charles |date=February 4, 2019 |website=AP NEWS |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2019, Belichick announced that he would assume another role as the Patriots defensive coordinator starting the 2019 season<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patriotswire.usatoday.com/2019/05/13/patriots-bill-belichick-playcaller/|title=Report: Bill Belichick to serve as Patriots defensive play-caller|date=May 13, 2019|publisher=}}</ref> On October 27, 2019, with the Patriots' win over the [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Belichick obtained his [[List of National Football League head coaches with 50 wins|300th win]] as a head coach.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hightower |first1=Kyle |title=Belichick wins 300th, perfect Patriots beat Browns 27-13 |url=https://news.yahoo.com/belichick-wins-300th-perfect-patriots-234416936.html |website=News.Yahoo.com |publisher=Yahoo! News |accessdate=October 27, 2019|date=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Sideline videotaping controversy====\n{{Main|2007 National Football League videotaping controversy}}\nIn an incident dubbed \"Spygate,\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Pedulla|first=Tom|title=Belichick apologizes for 'Videogate'|work=USA Today|date=September 12, 2007|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/patriots/2007-09-12-belichick-apology_N.htm}}</ref> on September 9, 2007, NFL security caught a Patriots video assistant taping the [[New York Jets]]' defensive signals from the sidelines, which is not an approved location. The NFL rules state \"No video recording devices of any kind are permitted to be in use in the coaches' booth, on the field, or in the locker room during the game.\" Jets coach [[Eric Mangini]], a former Patriots assistant, tipped off league officials that the Patriots might have been filming their signals. After the game, the Jets formally complained to the league.\n\nOn September 13, the NFL fined Belichick $500,000\u2014the largest fine ever imposed on a coach in the league's 87-year history,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3018338|title=Belichick draws $500,000 fine, but avoids suspension|publisher=Sports.espn.go.com|date=September 14, 2007|accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref> and fined the Patriots $250,000. Additionally, the Patriots forfeited their first round draft pick in the [[2008 NFL Draft]]. [[Roger Goodell]], a former employee of the Jets, said that he fined the Patriots as a team because Belichick exercises so much control over the Patriots' on-field operations that \"his actions and decisions are properly attributed to the club.\" Goodell considered suspending Belichick, but decided that taking away draft picks would be more severe in the long run.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2007/09/14/big_fines_for_belichick_team/|work=The Boston Globe|title=Big fines for Belichick, team|date=September 14, 2007|first1=Mike|last1=Reiss}}</ref> Gary Myers, ''[[New York Daily News]]'' columnist, stated Belichick should have been suspended by Goodell for the Patriots' next game against the Jets.<ref name=Myers_12_10_2007>{{cite news|last=Myers |first=Gary |title=Commissioner Goodell should have suspended Bill Belichick|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/jets/commissioner-goodell-suspended-bill-belichick-article-1.242700|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=December 10, 2007|accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBelichick later issued the following statement:\n\n{{quote|I accept full responsibility for the actions that led to tonight's ruling. Once again, I apologize to the Kraft family and every person directly or indirectly associated with the New England Patriots for the embarrassment, distraction and penalty my mistake caused. I also apologize to Patriots fans and would like to thank them for their support during the past few days and throughout my career. [...] As the Commissioner acknowledged, our use of sideline video had no impact on the outcome of last week's game. We have never used sideline video to obtain a competitive advantage while the game was in progress. [...] Part of my job as head coach is to ensure that our football operations are conducted in compliance of the league rules and all accepted interpretations of them. My interpretation of a rule in the Constitution and Bylaws was incorrect. [...] With tonight's resolution, I will not be offering any further comments on this matter. We are moving on with our preparations for Sunday's game.}}\n\nThe sanctions against Belichick were the harshest imposed on a head coach in league history until the [[New Orleans Saints]]' [[Sean Payton]] was suspended for the entire [[2012 NFL season|2012 season]] for covering up [[New Orleans Saints bounty scandal|a scheme in which bounties were paid]] for deliberately knocking opponents out of games.\n\nFollowing the incident and its fallout, Belichick led the Patriots to a perfect 16\u20130 regular season record, and was awarded the 2007 [[NFL Coach of the Year Award]], as voted on by the [[Associated Press]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3179438 Belichick voted coach of year for second time in four years]. ''[[ESPN]]'', Accessed January 2, 2008.</ref>\n\n====Overall record in New England====\nUnder Belichick, the Patriots have a regular-season record of 225\u201379\u20130 over 19 seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/BeliBi0.htm|title=Bill Belichick Record, Statistics, and Category Ranks \u2013 Pro-Football-Reference.com|website=Pro-Football-Reference|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref> Belichick is far and away the winningest coach in Patriots history; his 225 wins with the franchise are more than quadruple those of runner-up [[Mike Holovak]]. Belichick also has compiled a 30\u201310 record in the playoffs with New England, and 6\u20133 in Super Bowls. He has led the Patriots to 16 division titles, including five consecutive titles from [[2003 NFL season|2003]] to [[2007 NFL season|2007]] and eleven consecutive titles from [[2009 NFL season|2009]] to [[2019 NFL season|2019]]. Under Belichick, the team only missed the playoffs in 2000 and on tiebreakers in 2002 and 2008. Although missing qualifications for playoffs in 2002, the Patriots finished 2nd in the AFC east.\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! colspan=\"5\"|Regular season !! colspan=\"4\"|Postseason\n|-\n!Won!!Lost!!Ties